{"title_page": "Adam Schlesinger", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Adam Schlesinger\n| image            = Adam-Schlesinger-(in-Tinted-Windows).jpg\n| caption          = Schlesinger performing in 2009\n| birth_name       = Adam Lyons Schlesinger\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1967|10|31}}\n| birth_place      = New York City, New York, United States\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|4|1|1967|10|31}}\n| death_place      = \n| occupation       = Bassist, songwriter, composer, producer\n| years_active     = 1990\u20132020\n| instrument       = Bass guitar\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Power pop]]<ref name=all>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p194763/biography|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=December 26, 2009|website=[[AllMusic]]|title=Fountains of Wayne \u2013 Biography|first=Andrew|last=Leahey}}</ref> \n* [[alternative rock]]<ref name=all/> \n* [[geek rock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/blog/geekend/the-top-10-geek-rock-artists/|title=The top 10 geek rock artists|website=TechRepublic.com|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| awards           = Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics\n| associated_acts  = Fountains of Wayne, Tinted Windows (Since 2009), Ivy, Ivy (Since 1994), Fever High\n| background       = \n| Nationality      = American\n| Spouse           = Katherine Beinecke Michel (m. 1999)\n}}\n'''Adam Lyons Schlesinger'''<ref name=Smith /> (October 31, 1967 \u2013 April 1, 2020<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/arts/music/adam-schlesinger-dead-coronavirus.html</ref>) was an American singer-songwriter, record producer, and guitarist. He won three Emmys, a Grammy, and the ASCAP Pop Music Award, and was nominated for Oscar, Tony and Golden Globe Awards.\n\nHe was a founding member of the bands [[Fountains of Wayne]], [[Ivy (band)|Ivy]], and [[Tinted Windows (band)|Tinted Windows]]. He was a key songwriting contributor and producer for Brooklyn-based synth-pop duo [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]]. Schlesinger grew up in [[Manhattan]] and [[Montclair, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"eclectic\">{{cite news |last=Wise |first=Brian |title=Eclectic Sounds of New Jersey, Echoing From Coast to Coast |work=The New York Times |date=February 8, 2004 |accessdate=November 21, 2007 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E5DE163AF93BA35751C0A9629C8B63 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchlesinger grew up in [[Manhattan]] and [[Montclair, New Jersey]], where he attended [[Montclair High School (New Jersey)|Montclair High School]].<ref name=\"eclectic\" /> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Williams College]].\n\nOn January 30, 1999 Schlesinger married Katherine Michel, a graphic designer and [[Yale University|Yale]] graduate. They met in 1996 at WXOU Radio Bar,<ref name=Smith>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/14/style/vows-katherine-michel-adam-schlesinger.html|title= Vows; Katherine Michel, Adam Schlesinger|first=Lois Brady|last=Smith|publisher=New York Times|date=February 14, 1999|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> a bar that Schlesinger used to frequent with Fountains of Wayne co-founder [[Chris Collingwood]] when they were starting the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/features/fountains-of-wayne-2011-7/|title=Denizens of the Quotidian|first=Brian|last=Raftery|publisher=New York Magazine|date=July 10, 2011|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> They divorced in 2013. Schlesinger and Michel have two daughters, Sadie and Claire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/fountains-of-wayne-bassist-welcomes-baby-girl/|title=Fountains of Wayne Bassist Welcomes Baby Girl|first=Brian|last=Orloff|publisher=People|date=March 8, 2007|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSchlesinger was a cousin of [[Jon Bernthal]], an [[actor]] who is best known for his roles as [[Shane Walsh (The Walking Dead)|Shane Walsh]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'' and [[Punisher|The Punisher/Frank Castle]] in [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' and ''[[The Punisher (TV series)|The Punisher]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.aol.com/artist/adam-schlesinger/biography |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120713190235/http://music.aol.com/artist/adam-schlesinger/biography |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 13, 2012 |title=AOL - News, Sports, Weather, Entertainment, Local & Lifestyle |publisher=Music.aol.com |accessdate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref> He was also the grandson of [[Murray Bernthal]] (1911\u20132010), a musician and producer who was long active in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=broadwayworld>{{cite web |url=http://centralnewyork.broadwayworld.com/article/Murray_Bernthal_Dies_at_99_20101210 |date=December 11, 2010 |title=Murray Bernthal dies at 99 |author= |publisher=BWW News Desk}}. Adam graduated from [[Williams College]] in Williamstown, MA.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Schlesinger was hospitalized and placed on a ventilator after contracting [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-coma-fountains-of-wayne-emmy-winner-1203549825/|title=Adam Schlesinger, Fountains of Wayne Co-Founder, Hospitalized With Coronavirus|author=Jem Aswad, Chris|website=Variety.com|date=2020-03-31|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Willman|first3=Chris}}</ref> \n\n===Death===\nOn 1 April 2020, Schlesinger died at the age of 52 as a result of health complications caused by [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-dead-dies-1203552130/|title=Adam Schlesinger Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 52|last=Willman|first=Chris|website=Variety.com|date=April 1, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sisario|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/arts/music/adam-schlesinger-dead-coronavirus.html|title=Adam Schlesinger, Songwriter for Rock, Film and the Stage, Dies at 52|date=2020-04-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nSchlesinger was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Rich |last=Drees |title=That Tune You Do: Writing The Music For That Thing You Do |work=FilmBuffOnline |url=http://www.filmbuffonline.com/Features/ThatTuneYouDo.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127102824/http://www.filmbuffonline.com/Features/ThatTuneYouDo.htm |archivedate=November 27, 2007 }}</ref> and a [[Golden Globe Award]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Schlesinger: Those Things He Do |first=Jem |last=Aswad |work=The American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers |url=http://ascap.com/musicbiz/schlesinger.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117054109/http://www.ascap.com/musicbiz/schlesinger.html |archivedate=January 17, 2008 }}</ref> in 1997 for writing the title track of the [[Tom Hanks]]-directed film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]''<ref name=\"ktvu\">{{cite web|title=KTVU.com Talks To Fountains Of Wayne's Adam Schlesinger |work=KTVU |url=http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/13554930/detail.html |date=June 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511220051/http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/13554930/detail.html |archivedate=May 11, 2008 }}</ref> as well as two other songs for the film.\n\nFountains of Wayne was nominated for two [[Grammy Award]]s in 2003 for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]] for \"Stacy's Mom\".<ref>{{cite news|title=OutKast leads Grammy nods |work=CNN |date=December 4, 2003 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/04/grammy.nominations/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050407102217/http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/04/grammy.nominations/index.html |archivedate=April 7, 2005 }}</ref>\n\nSchlesinger and [[David Javerbaum]] received two Tony nominations in 2008 [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]] and [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] for the musical ''[[Cry-Baby (musical)|Cry-Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title='In the Heights' heads list of Tony nominees |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Today.com |date=May 13, 2008 |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/heights-heads-list-tony-nominees-wbna24594561 }}</ref> They also received a 2009 Emmy nomination for Outstanding Music And Lyrics, for their song \"Much Worse Things\", performed by [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Stephen Colbert]] on the television special and album ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'' The album, co-written by Schlesinger and Javerbaum, and co-produced by Schlesinger and Steven M. Gold, also won the 2009 [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]].\n\nSchlesinger received a 2013 Daytime Emmy nomination for Outstanding Original Song for his \"Elmo The Musical\" theme for ''[[Sesame Street]]''. He and Molly Boylan received a 2011 [[Daytime Emmy]] nomination for the song \"I Wonder\" from ''[[Sesame Street]]''.\n\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum received a 2012 [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Music And Lyrics for their song \"It's Not Just For Gays Anymore\", performed by [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as the opening number of the [[65th Tony Awards]] telecast; and a 2013 Emmy Award for Outstanding Music And Lyrics for their song \"If I Had Time\", performed by [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as the closing number of the [[65th Tony Awards|66th Tony Awards]] telecast.\n\nSchlesinger received two 2016 Emmy nominations for his work on the CW series ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend'': Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics for \"Settle For Me\" (co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen), and Outstanding Main Title Theme (co-written with Rachel Bloom).\n\nHe received a 2017 Emmy nomination for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics for \"We Tapped That Ass\" (co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen) from the CW series ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.''\n\nHe won the 2019 Emmy award for Outstanding Original Music And Lyrics for \"Antidepressants Are So Not A Big Deal\", and was also nominated for Outstanding Original Main Title Theme Music for \"Meet Rebecca\" (Season 4 Theme) from ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.'' (Both co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen)\n\n==Songwriting==\n\n===In films===\nIn addition to writing and co-producing the [[That Thing You Do (song)|title song]] to ''[[That Thing You Do!]]'', he composed \"Master Of The Seas\" for ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]'' performed by [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Peter Dinklage]] and others. He wrote and produced three songs for ''[[Music and Lyrics]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Creating some 'Music and Lyrics' |first=Todd |last=Leopold |work=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/04/03/sidebar.schlesinger/index.html |date=April 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"av\" /> and his music has also been featured in films such as ''[[Shallow Hal]]'' (which he scored with Ivy);<ref name=\"catchy\">{{cite news |title=Songwriter Schlesinger: His Expertise Is Catchy |first=Sean |last=Daly |work=The Washington Post |date=April 3, 2005 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A18956-2005Apr1.html }}</ref> ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Robots |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808512304/cast |accessdate=February 4, 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080223002109/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808512304/cast| archivedate= February 23, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'';<ref name=\"catchy\" /> ''[[Me, Myself & Irene]]'';<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite news|title=The Music \u2014 and Lyrics \u2014 Man |first=Glenn |last=Kenny |work=Premiere.com |publisher=Hachette Filipacchi Media U.S., Inc. |url=http://www.premiere.com/features/3784/the-music-151-and-lyrics-151-man.html |accessdate=February 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123235809/http://www.premiere.com/features/3784/the-music-151-and-lyrics-151-man.html |archivedate=November 23, 2007 }}</ref> ''[[Josie and the Pussycats (film)|Josie and the Pussycats]]'';<ref name=\"av\">{{cite news|title=Interview with Adam Schlesinger |first=Nathan |last=Rabin |url=https://www.avclub.com/content/interview/adam_schlesinger |work=A.V. Club |date=April 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128141205/http://www.avclub.com/content/interview/adam_schlesinger |archivedate=January 28, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Scary Movie]]'';<ref name=\"natn\">{{cite news|title=Andy Chase, Dominique Durand and Adam Schlesinger: No Distance Too Far |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |work=Nude as the News |url=http://www.nudeasthenews.com/interviews/30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511215348/http://www.nudeasthenews.com/interviews/30 |archivedate=May 11, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Art School Confidential (film)|Art School Confidential]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Art School Confidential |work=Yahoo! Movies |accessdate=February 4, 2008 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808628304/cast }}</ref> ''[[Fever Pitch (2005 film)|Fever Pitch]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=Music and Lyrics: Comedy's catchy, but not classic |first=Barbara |last=Vancheri |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=February 14, 2007 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07045/761829-120.stm }}</ref> ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (2004 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=A Chat With Adam Schlesinger |first=Will |last=Harris |date=April 5, 2007 |work=Bullz-Eye.com |url=http://www.bullz-eye.com/music/interviews/2007/adam_schlesinger.htm }}</ref> ''[[Because of Winn-Dixie (film)|Because of Winn-Dixie]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=Harris, Colvin, Finns Whistle 'Dixie' |date=November 30, 2004 |first=Carla |last=Hay |work=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65460/harris-colvin-finns-whistle-dixie }}</ref> ''[[Orange County (film)|Orange County]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Orange County |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1807736420/cast |accessdate=February 4, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Two Weeks Notice]]'',<ref name=\"premiere\" /> and others.\n\n===Songs performed by other artists===\n* \"Our Own World\" and \"I Was There\" and \"House Of Broken Gingerbread\" [[The Monkees]]\n* \"[[Just The Girl]]\" and \"I'll Take My Chances\" for [[The Click Five]]\n* \"Everybody Loves Music\" by Nicki Minaj, Pat Monahan, and Ken Jeong on \"The Billboard Music Awards\"\n* \"I Guess Its American\" for [[Superdrag]] (co-written with John Davis)\n* \"[[High School Never Ends]]\" with [[Bowling For Soup]] (co-written with [[Jaret Reddick]])\n* \"I Am What I Am\" for the [[Jonas Brothers]]\n* \"Hackensack\" (Fountains Of Wayne cover) by [[Katy Perry]]\n* \"Perfect Night\" by Sarah Silverman and will.i.am\n* \"1-800 Clap Your Hands\", \"Marisol\", \"You Get Me Through\", \"Double Talk\", and \"Jerkface Loser Boyfriend\"  by [[Emily Osment]]\n* \"Work to Do\" for [[America (band)|America]]\n* Eight songs for [[Stephen Colbert]]'s television special ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'' performed by Stephen Colbert, [[Jon Stewart]], [[Feist (singer)|Feist]], [[John Legend]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Toby Keith]] (co-written with David Javerbaum).\n* \"Barbie Eat a Sandwich\" and \"My Problems\" with [[Care Bears On Fire]]\n* \"A Little More Us\" by Stereo Skyline\n*\"Just Like a Rockstar\" by [[The Fresh Beat Band]]\n* \"Stay In Our PJs\" by Big Time Rush\n* \"I'll Say It\" by [[Kathy Griffin]]\n* \"Text Me Merry Christmas\" by Straight No Chaser feat. [[Kristen Bell]]\n* \"Tantalized\", \"All Work\", \"That's So Typical\", \"Spit It Out\", \"Looks Good On Paper\" by [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]]\n\n===In theatre===\nSchlesinger and ''[[The Daily Show]]'' executive producer [[David Javerbaum]] co-wrote the songs for the musical theater adaptation of the [[John Waters]] film ''Cry-Baby''.<ref name=\"playhouse\">{{cite press release|title=La Jolla Playhouse Presents Broadway-Bound Cry-Baby |work=La Jolla Playhouse |date=September 27, 2007 |url=http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/PR/DownloadReleases/CryBabyRelease.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124085114/http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/PR/DownloadReleases/CryBabyRelease.pdf |archivedate=January 24, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Cry-Baby (musical)|Cry-Baby]]'' debuted at the [[La Jolla Playhouse]] in [[La Jolla]], [[California]], in November 2007.<ref name=\"playhouse\" />  Previews for the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] run began at the [[Marquis Theatre]] on March 15, 2008. Its official opening night was April 24, 2008.<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/production.asp?ID=476233 Cry-Baby] at the [[Internet Broadway Database]]</ref>\n\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum co-wrote the closing song \"I Have Faith In You\" for Javerbaum's play ''An Act Of God'' which opened on Broadway on May 28, 2015. The song is performed by [[Jim Parsons]], Chris Fitzgerald, and Tim Kazurinsky.\n\nSchlesinger and [[Sarah Silverman]] are currently working on a musical entitled ''The Bedwetter'', based on her book of the same name.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greene |first=Andy |title=Sarah Silverman: 'I'm the Poorest Famous Person in the World' |work=Rolling Stone |date=February 13, 2014 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/sarah-silverman-im-the-poorest-famous-person-in-the-world-20140213 }}</ref> The musical is set for previews to begin on May 9, 2020 at the Atlantic's Linda Gross Theater; opening night is scheduled for Wednesday, June 10, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/sarah-silverman-off-broadway-musical-bedwetter-premiere-date-1202625281/|title=Sarah Silverman Musical \u2018The Bedwetter\u2019 Sets Off Broadway Premiere Date|first1=Greg|last1=Evans|website=Deadline.com|date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===In television===\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum co-wrote the opening number of the 2011 Tony Awards ceremony, \"It's Not Just For Gays Anymore\", as well as the opening and closing numbers of the 2012 Tony Awards, \"What If Life Were More Like Theater\" and \"If I Had Time\", all performed by Neil Patrick Harris. They also wrote the opening number of the 2011 Emmy Awards, \"TV Is A Vast Wonderland\", performed by [[Jane Lynch]]; and \"The Number In The Middle Of The Show\", performed at the 2013 Emmy Awards by Neil Patrick Harris, Sarah Silverman, and [[Nathan Fillion]].\n\nSchlesinger's television composing work includes theme music, songs, and/or score for ''I Love You America'' (Hulu), ''The Maya Rudolph Show'' (NBC), ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'', the 2011 and 2012 Tony Awards, the 2011 and 2013 Emmy Awards, ''Big Time Rush'', ''T.U.F.F. Puppy'' (Nickelodeon), ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'' (Disney Channel), ''Fresh Beat Band'' (Nickelodeon), ''[[Kathy (TV series)|Kathy]]'' (Bravo), ''[[Crank Yankers]]'', \"Wedding Band\" (TBS), the Billboard Music Awards, ''[[Bubble Guppies]]'' (Nick Jr.), ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', ''[[Sesame Street]]'', Comedy Central's \"Night Of Too Many Stars\", Robert Smigel's cartoons for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', The Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade with Neil Patrick Harris, the Comedy Awards (Comedy Central), ''American Dreams'', [[Stephen King]]'s ''[[Kingdom Hospital]]'', ''The In-Laws'', ''[[The Man Show]]'', ''[[Too Late with Adam Carolla]]'', ''[[The Dana Carvey Show]]'', ''John Leguizamo's House Of Buggin''', ''My Kind of Town'', and others. His songs have also been licensed for use on numerous television series including ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl (TV series)|Gossip Girl]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'', ''Roswell'', and others.\n\nHe wrote songs for, and was Executive Music Producer of, the scripted comedy ''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend (TV series)|Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]'' on The CW Network.\n\n==Production work==\nAs a record producer and mixer, he has worked with [[The Monkees]], [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Swirl 360]], [[Tahiti 80]], [[Motion City Soundtrack]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Motion City Soundtrack: Full Biography |work=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/motion_city_soundtrack/artist.jhtml }}</ref> [[Verve Pipe]],<ref name=\"natn\" /> [[Robert Plant]], [[America (band)|America]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Schlesinger, Iha Producing New America Disc |work=Billboard |date=January 17, 2006 |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60012/schlesinger-iha-producing-new-america-disc }}</ref> [[The Sounds]], [[They Might Be Giants]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Schlesinger: Welcome Interstate Musicians |work=Harp |first=Alan |last=Di Perna |issue=November/December 2004 |url=https://www.harpmagazine.com/reviews/cd_reviews/detail.cfm?article_id=2415 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Fastball (band)|Fastball]], and many other artists, as well as producing or co-producing five Fountains of Wayne and five Ivy albums.\n\n==Side projects==\nSchlesinger was also in a side project band called [[Tinted Windows (band)|Tinted Windows]] formed by guitarist [[James Iha]], previously of [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] and [[A Perfect Circle]], singer [[Taylor Hanson]] of [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]], and [[Bun E. Carlos]] of [[Cheap Trick]], and recorded and toured with them in 2009 and 2010. He also contributed to Iha's second solo album, ''[[Look to the Sky]]'' (2012).\n\nHe was the main composer and producer for Brooklyn-based synth-pop duo [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090120143401/http://laist.com/2009/01/16/interview_adam_schlesinger_of_fount.php LAist Interview with Adam Schlesinger of Fountains of Wayne]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0772245}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Adam Schlesinger}}\n\n{{Fountains of Wayne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schlesinger, Adam}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Williams College alumni]]\n[[Category:Montclair High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Fountains of Wayne members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tinted Windows (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Adam Schlesinger\n| image            = Adam-Schlesinger-(in-Tinted-Windows).jpg\n| caption          = Schlesinger performing in 2009\n| birth_name       = Adam Lyons Schlesinger\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1967|10|31}}\n| birth_place      = New York City, New York, United States\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|4|1|1967|10|31}}\n| death_place      = \n| occupation       = Bassist, songwriter, composer, producer\n| years_active     = 1990\u20132020\n| instrument       = Bass guitar\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Power pop]]<ref name=all>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p194763/biography|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=December 26, 2009|website=[[AllMusic]]|title=Fountains of Wayne \u2013 Biography|first=Andrew|last=Leahey}}</ref> \n* [[alternative rock]]<ref name=all/> \n* [[geek rock]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techrepublic.com/blog/geekend/the-top-10-geek-rock-artists/|title=The top 10 geek rock artists|website=TechRepublic.com|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n| awards           = Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Award for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics\n| associated_acts  = Fountains of Wayne, Tinted Windows (Since 2009), Ivy, Ivy (Since 1994), Fever High\n| background       = \n| Nationality      = American\n| Spouse           = Katherine Beinecke Michel (m. 1999)\n}}\n'''Adam Lyons Schlesinger'''<ref name=Smith /> (October 31, 1967 \u2013 April 1, 2020<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/arts/music/adam-schlesinger-dead-coronavirus.html</ref>) was an American singer-songwriter, record producer, and guitarist. He won three Emmys, a Grammy, and the ASCAP Pop Music Award, and was nominated for Oscar, Tony and Golden Globe Awards.\n\nHe was a founding member of the bands [[Fountains of Wayne]], [[Ivy (band)|Ivy]], and [[Tinted Windows (band)|Tinted Windows]]. He was a key songwriting contributor and producer for Brooklyn-based synth-pop duo [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]]. Schlesinger grew up in [[Manhattan]] and [[Montclair, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"eclectic\">{{cite news |last=Wise |first=Brian |title=Eclectic Sounds of New Jersey, Echoing From Coast to Coast |work=The New York Times |date=February 8, 2004 |accessdate=November 21, 2007 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F04E5DE163AF93BA35751C0A9629C8B63 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchlesinger grew up in [[Manhattan]] and [[Montclair, New Jersey]], where he attended [[Montclair High School (New Jersey)|Montclair High School]].<ref name=\"eclectic\" /> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Williams College]].\n\nOn January 30, 1999 Schlesinger married Katherine Michel, a graphic designer and [[Yale University|Yale]] graduate. They met in 1996 at WXOU Radio Bar,<ref name=Smith>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/14/style/vows-katherine-michel-adam-schlesinger.html|title= Vows; Katherine Michel, Adam Schlesinger|first=Lois Brady|last=Smith|publisher=New York Times|date=February 14, 1999|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> a bar that Schlesinger used to frequent with Fountains of Wayne co-founder [[Chris Collingwood]] when they were starting the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/popmusic/features/fountains-of-wayne-2011-7/|title=Denizens of the Quotidian|first=Brian|last=Raftery|publisher=New York Magazine|date=July 10, 2011|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> They divorced in 2013. Schlesinger and Michel have two daughters, Sadie and Claire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/fountains-of-wayne-bassist-welcomes-baby-girl/|title=Fountains of Wayne Bassist Welcomes Baby Girl|first=Brian|last=Orloff|publisher=People|date=March 8, 2007|accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSchlesinger was a cousin of [[Jon Bernthal]], an [[actor]] who is best known for his roles as [[Shane Walsh (The Walking Dead)|Shane Walsh]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'' and [[Punisher|The Punisher/Frank Castle]] in [[Netflix]]'s ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' and ''[[The Punisher (TV series)|The Punisher]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.aol.com/artist/adam-schlesinger/biography |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120713190235/http://music.aol.com/artist/adam-schlesinger/biography |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 13, 2012 |title=AOL - News, Sports, Weather, Entertainment, Local & Lifestyle |publisher=Music.aol.com |accessdate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref> He was also the grandson of [[Murray Bernthal]] (1911\u20132010), a musician and producer who was long active in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=broadwayworld>{{cite web |url=http://centralnewyork.broadwayworld.com/article/Murray_Bernthal_Dies_at_99_20101210 |date=December 11, 2010 |title=Murray Bernthal dies at 99 |author= |publisher=BWW News Desk}}. Adam graduated from [[Williams College]] in Williamstown, MA.</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Schlesinger was hospitalized and placed on a ventilator after contracting [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-coma-fountains-of-wayne-emmy-winner-1203549825/|title=Adam Schlesinger, Fountains of Wayne Co-Founder, Hospitalized With Coronavirus|author=Jem Aswad, Chris|website=Variety.com|date=2020-03-31|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Willman|first3=Chris}}</ref> \n\n===Death===\nOn 1 April 2020, Schlesinger died at the age of 52 as a result of health complications caused by [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/adam-schlesinger-coronavirus-dead-dies-1203552130/|title=Adam Schlesinger Dies of Coronavirus Complications at 52|last=Willman|first=Chris|website=Variety.com|date=April 1, 2020|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sisario|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/01/arts/music/adam-schlesinger-dead-coronavirus.html|title=Adam Schlesinger, Songwriter for Rock, Film and the Stage, Dies at 52|date=2020-04-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-01|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nSchlesinger was nominated for an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]<ref>{{cite news |first=Rich |last=Drees |title=That Tune You Do: Writing The Music For That Thing You Do |work=FilmBuffOnline |url=http://www.filmbuffonline.com/Features/ThatTuneYouDo.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127102824/http://www.filmbuffonline.com/Features/ThatTuneYouDo.htm |archivedate=November 27, 2007 }}</ref> and a [[Golden Globe Award]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Adam Schlesinger: Those Things He Do |first=Jem |last=Aswad |work=The American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers |url=http://ascap.com/musicbiz/schlesinger.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117054109/http://www.ascap.com/musicbiz/schlesinger.html |archivedate=January 17, 2008 }}</ref> in 1997 for writing the title track of the [[Tom Hanks]]-directed film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]''<ref name=\"ktvu\">{{cite web|title=KTVU.com Talks To Fountains Of Wayne's Adam Schlesinger |work=KTVU |url=http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/13554930/detail.html |date=June 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511220051/http://www.ktvu.com/entertainment/13554930/detail.html |archivedate=May 11, 2008 }}</ref> as well as two other songs for the film.\n\nFountains of Wayne was nominated for two [[Grammy Award]]s in 2003 for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]] for \"Stacy's Mom\".<ref>{{cite news|title=OutKast leads Grammy nods |work=CNN |date=December 4, 2003 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/04/grammy.nominations/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050407102217/http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/04/grammy.nominations/index.html |archivedate=April 7, 2005 }}</ref>\n\nSchlesinger and [[David Javerbaum]] received two Tony nominations in 2008 [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]] and [[Tony Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] for the musical ''[[Cry-Baby (musical)|Cry-Baby]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title='In the Heights' heads list of Tony nominees |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Today.com |date=May 13, 2008 |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/heights-heads-list-tony-nominees-wbna24594561 }}</ref> They also received a 2009 Emmy nomination for Outstanding Music And Lyrics, for their song \"Much Worse Things\", performed by [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Stephen Colbert]] on the television special and album ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'' The album, co-written by Schlesinger and Javerbaum, and co-produced by Schlesinger and Steven M. Gold, also won the 2009 [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]].\n\nSchlesinger received a 2013 Daytime Emmy nomination for Outstanding Original Song for his \"Elmo The Musical\" theme for ''[[Sesame Street]]''. He and Molly Boylan received a 2011 [[Daytime Emmy]] nomination for the song \"I Wonder\" from ''[[Sesame Street]]''.\n\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum received a 2012 [[Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Music And Lyrics for their song \"It's Not Just For Gays Anymore\", performed by [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as the opening number of the [[65th Tony Awards]] telecast; and a 2013 Emmy Award for Outstanding Music And Lyrics for their song \"If I Had Time\", performed by [[Neil Patrick Harris]] as the closing number of the [[65th Tony Awards|66th Tony Awards]] telecast.\n\nSchlesinger received two 2016 Emmy nominations for his work on the CW series ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend'': Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics for \"Settle For Me\" (co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen), and Outstanding Main Title Theme (co-written with Rachel Bloom).\n\nHe received a 2017 Emmy nomination for Outstanding Original Music and Lyrics for \"We Tapped That Ass\" (co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen) from the CW series ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.''\n\nHe won the 2019 Emmy award for Outstanding Original Music And Lyrics for \"Antidepressants Are So Not A Big Deal\", and was also nominated for Outstanding Original Main Title Theme Music for \"Meet Rebecca\" (Season 4 Theme) from ''Crazy Ex-Girlfriend.'' (Both co-written with Rachel Bloom and Jack Dolgen)\n\n==Songwriting==\n\n===In films===\nIn addition to writing and co-producing the [[That Thing You Do (song)|title song]] to ''[[That Thing You Do!]]'', he composed \"Master Of The Seas\" for ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]'' performed by [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Peter Dinklage]] and others. He wrote and produced three songs for ''[[Music and Lyrics]]'',<ref>{{cite news |title=Creating some 'Music and Lyrics' |first=Todd |last=Leopold |work=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/04/03/sidebar.schlesinger/index.html |date=April 3, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"av\" /> and his music has also been featured in films such as ''[[Shallow Hal]]'' (which he scored with Ivy);<ref name=\"catchy\">{{cite news |title=Songwriter Schlesinger: His Expertise Is Catchy |first=Sean |last=Daly |work=The Washington Post |date=April 3, 2005 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A18956-2005Apr1.html }}</ref> ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Robots |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808512304/cast |accessdate=February 4, 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080223002109/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808512304/cast| archivedate= February 23, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'';<ref name=\"catchy\" /> ''[[Me, Myself & Irene]]'';<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite news|title=The Music \u2014 and Lyrics \u2014 Man |first=Glenn |last=Kenny |work=Premiere.com |publisher=Hachette Filipacchi Media U.S., Inc. |url=http://www.premiere.com/features/3784/the-music-151-and-lyrics-151-man.html |accessdate=February 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123235809/http://www.premiere.com/features/3784/the-music-151-and-lyrics-151-man.html |archivedate=November 23, 2007 }}</ref> ''[[Josie and the Pussycats (film)|Josie and the Pussycats]]'';<ref name=\"av\">{{cite news|title=Interview with Adam Schlesinger |first=Nathan |last=Rabin |url=https://www.avclub.com/content/interview/adam_schlesinger |work=A.V. Club |date=April 25, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080128141205/http://www.avclub.com/content/interview/adam_schlesinger |archivedate=January 28, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Scary Movie]]'';<ref name=\"natn\">{{cite news|title=Andy Chase, Dominique Durand and Adam Schlesinger: No Distance Too Far |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |work=Nude as the News |url=http://www.nudeasthenews.com/interviews/30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511215348/http://www.nudeasthenews.com/interviews/30 |archivedate=May 11, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Art School Confidential (film)|Art School Confidential]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Art School Confidential |work=Yahoo! Movies |accessdate=February 4, 2008 |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1808628304/cast }}</ref> ''[[Fever Pitch (2005 film)|Fever Pitch]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=Music and Lyrics: Comedy's catchy, but not classic |first=Barbara |last=Vancheri |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=February 14, 2007 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07045/761829-120.stm }}</ref> ''[[The Manchurian Candidate (2004 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=A Chat With Adam Schlesinger |first=Will |last=Harris |date=April 5, 2007 |work=Bullz-Eye.com |url=http://www.bullz-eye.com/music/interviews/2007/adam_schlesinger.htm }}</ref> ''[[Because of Winn-Dixie (film)|Because of Winn-Dixie]]'';<ref>{{cite news |title=Harris, Colvin, Finns Whistle 'Dixie' |date=November 30, 2004 |first=Carla |last=Hay |work=Billboard |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65460/harris-colvin-finns-whistle-dixie }}</ref> ''[[Orange County (film)|Orange County]]'';<ref>{{cite web |title=Orange County |work=Yahoo! Movies |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1807736420/cast |accessdate=February 4, 2008 }}</ref> ''[[Two Weeks Notice]]'',<ref name=\"premiere\" /> and others.\n\n===Songs performed by other artists===\n* \"Our Own World\" and \"I Was There\" and \"House Of Broken Gingerbread\" [[The Monkees]]\n* \"[[Just The Girl]]\" and \"I'll Take My Chances\" for [[The Click Five]]\n* \"Everybody Loves Music\" by Nicki Minaj, Pat Monahan, and Ken Jeong on \"The Billboard Music Awards\"\n* \"I Guess Its American\" for [[Superdrag]] (co-written with John Davis)\n* \"[[High School Never Ends]]\" with [[Bowling For Soup]] (co-written with [[Jaret Reddick]])\n* \"I Am What I Am\" for the [[Jonas Brothers]]\n* \"Hackensack\" (Fountains Of Wayne cover) by [[Katy Perry]]\n* \"Perfect Night\" by Sarah Silverman and will.i.am\n* \"1-800 Clap Your Hands\", \"Marisol\", \"You Get Me Through\", \"Double Talk\", and \"Jerkface Loser Boyfriend\"  by [[Emily Osment]]\n* \"Work To Do\" for [[America (band)|America]]\n* Eight songs for [[Stephen Colbert]]'s television special ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'' performed by Stephen Colbert, [[Jon Stewart]], [[Feist (singer)|Feist]], [[John Legend]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Toby Keith]] (co-written with David Javerbaum).\n* \"Barbie Eat A Sandwich\" and \"My Problems\" with [[Care Bears On Fire]]\n* \"A Little More Us\" by Stereo Skyline\n*\"Just Like A Rockstar\" by [[The Fresh Beat Band]]\n* \"Stay In Our PJs\" by Big Time Rush\n* \"I'll Say It\" by [[Kathy Griffin]]\n* \"Text Me Merry Christmas\" by Straight No Chaser feat. [[Kristen Bell]]\n* \"Tantalized\", \"All Work\", \"That's So Typical\", \"Spit It Out\", \"Looks Good On Paper\" by [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]]\n\n===In theatre===\nSchlesinger and ''[[The Daily Show]]'' executive producer [[David Javerbaum]] co-wrote the songs for the musical theater adaptation of the [[John Waters]] film ''Cry-Baby''.<ref name=\"playhouse\">{{cite press release|title=La Jolla Playhouse Presents Broadway-Bound Cry-Baby |work=La Jolla Playhouse |date=September 27, 2007 |url=http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/PR/DownloadReleases/CryBabyRelease.pdf |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124085114/http://www.lajollaplayhouse.org/PR/DownloadReleases/CryBabyRelease.pdf |archivedate=January 24, 2009 }}</ref> ''[[Cry-Baby (musical)|Cry-Baby]]'' debuted at the [[La Jolla Playhouse]] in [[La Jolla]], [[California]], in November 2007.<ref name=\"playhouse\" />  Previews for the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] run began at the [[Marquis Theatre]] on March 15, 2008. Its official opening night was April 24, 2008.<ref>[http://www.ibdb.com/production.asp?ID=476233 Cry-Baby] at the [[Internet Broadway Database]]</ref>\n\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum co-wrote the closing song \"I Have Faith In You\" for Javerbaum's play ''An Act Of God'' which opened on Broadway on May 28, 2015. The song is performed by [[Jim Parsons]], Chris Fitzgerald, and Tim Kazurinsky.\n\nSchlesinger and [[Sarah Silverman]] are currently working on a musical entitled ''The Bedwetter'', based on her book of the same name.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greene |first=Andy |title=Sarah Silverman: 'I'm the Poorest Famous Person in the World' |work=Rolling Stone |date=February 13, 2014 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/sarah-silverman-im-the-poorest-famous-person-in-the-world-20140213 }}</ref> The musical is set for previews to begin on May 9, 2020 at the Atlantic's Linda Gross Theater; opening night is scheduled for Wednesday, June 10, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/sarah-silverman-off-broadway-musical-bedwetter-premiere-date-1202625281/|title=Sarah Silverman Musical \u2018The Bedwetter\u2019 Sets Off Broadway Premiere Date|first1=Greg|last1=Evans|website=Deadline.com|date=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===In television===\nSchlesinger and Javerbaum co-wrote the opening number of the 2011 Tony Awards ceremony, \"It's Not Just For Gays Anymore\", as well as the opening and closing numbers of the 2012 Tony Awards, \"What If Life Were More Like Theater\" and \"If I Had Time\", all performed by Neil Patrick Harris. They also wrote the opening number of the 2011 Emmy Awards, \"TV Is A Vast Wonderland\", performed by [[Jane Lynch]]; and \"The Number In The Middle Of The Show\", performed at the 2013 Emmy Awards by Neil Patrick Harris, Sarah Silverman, and [[Nathan Fillion]].\n\nSchlesinger's television composing work includes theme music, songs, and/or score for ''I Love You America'' (Hulu), ''The Maya Rudolph Show'' (NBC), ''[[A Colbert Christmas: The Greatest Gift of All!]]'', the 2011 and 2012 Tony Awards, the 2011 and 2013 Emmy Awards, ''Big Time Rush'', ''T.U.F.F. Puppy'' (Nickelodeon), ''[[Good Luck Charlie]]'' (Disney Channel), ''Fresh Beat Band'' (Nickelodeon), ''[[Kathy (TV series)|Kathy]]'' (Bravo), ''[[Crank Yankers]]'', \"Wedding Band\" (TBS), the Billboard Music Awards, ''[[Bubble Guppies]]'' (Nick Jr.), ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', ''[[Sesame Street]]'', Comedy Central's \"Night Of Too Many Stars\", Robert Smigel's cartoons for ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', The Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade with Neil Patrick Harris, the Comedy Awards (Comedy Central), ''American Dreams'', [[Stephen King]]'s ''[[Kingdom Hospital]]'', ''The In-Laws'', ''[[The Man Show]]'', ''[[Too Late with Adam Carolla]]'', ''[[The Dana Carvey Show]]'', ''John Leguizamo's House Of Buggin''', ''My Kind of Town'', and others. His songs have also been licensed for use on numerous television series including ''[[Scrubs (TV series)|Scrubs]]'', ''[[The Hills (TV series)|The Hills]]'', ''[[Gossip Girl (TV series)|Gossip Girl]]'', ''[[Melrose Place]]'', ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'', ''Roswell'', and others.\n\nHe wrote songs for, and was Executive Music Producer of, the scripted comedy ''[[Crazy Ex-Girlfriend (TV series)|Crazy Ex-Girlfriend]]'' on The CW Network.\n\n==Production work==\nAs a record producer and mixer, he has worked with [[The Monkees]], [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Swirl 360]], [[Tahiti 80]], [[Motion City Soundtrack]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Motion City Soundtrack: Full Biography |work=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/motion_city_soundtrack/artist.jhtml }}</ref> [[Verve Pipe]],<ref name=\"natn\" /> [[Robert Plant]], [[America (band)|America]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Schlesinger, Iha Producing New America Disc |work=Billboard |date=January 17, 2006 |first=Jonathan |last=Cohen |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60012/schlesinger-iha-producing-new-america-disc }}</ref> [[The Sounds]], [[They Might Be Giants]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Adam Schlesinger: Welcome Interstate Musicians |work=Harp |first=Alan |last=Di Perna |issue=November/December 2004 |url=https://www.harpmagazine.com/reviews/cd_reviews/detail.cfm?article_id=2415 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Fastball (band)|Fastball]], and many other artists, as well as producing or co-producing five Fountains of Wayne and five Ivy albums.\n\n==Side projects==\nSchlesinger was also in a side project band called [[Tinted Windows (band)|Tinted Windows]] formed by guitarist [[James Iha]], previously of [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] and [[A Perfect Circle]], singer [[Taylor Hanson]] of [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]], and [[Bun E. Carlos]] of [[Cheap Trick]], and recorded and toured with them in 2009 and 2010. He also contributed to Iha's second solo album, ''[[Look to the Sky]]'' (2012).\n\nHe was the main composer and producer for Brooklyn-based synth-pop duo [[Fever High (Band)|Fever High]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090120143401/http://laist.com/2009/01/16/interview_adam_schlesinger_of_fount.php LAist Interview with Adam Schlesinger of Fountains of Wayne]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{IMDb name|0772245}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Adam Schlesinger}}\n\n{{Fountains of Wayne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schlesinger, Adam}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Williams College alumni]]\n[[Category:Montclair High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Montclair, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Fountains of Wayne members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Tinted Windows (band) members]]\n", "name_user": "Koavf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSongs performed by other artists", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Schlesinger"}
{"title_page": "The Young Turks", "text_new": "{{About|the political commentary web series|the Turkish reform movement|Young Turks|other meanings|Young Turks (disambiguation)|other meanings|TYT}}\n{{Short description|Online news show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Young Turks\n| image                    = TYT logo.svg\n| caption                  = Logotype\n| show_name_2              = TYT\n| genre                    = [[Political commentary]]<br/>[[News]]<ref name=\"PaoGhuHar2637\">{{cite journal|last1=Paolillo|first1=John|last2=Ghule|first2=Sharad|last3=Harper|first3=Brian|date=2019|title=A network view of social media platform history: Social structure, dynamics and content on Youtube|url=https://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/bitstream/10125/59701/0261.pdf|publisher=Proceedings of the 52nd Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences|accessdate=23 February 2020|pages=2637|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| creator                  = [[Cenk Uygur]]<br/>[[Ben Mankiewicz]]<ref name=\"Show\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks: Rebel Headquarters : News : Politics : Commentary |url=http://www.theyoungturks.com/show/index.htm |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515140446/http://www.theyoungturks.com/show/index.htm |archive-date=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br/>Dave Koller<ref name=\"Show\"/>\n| director                 = Jesus Godoy<ref name=\"Show\"/><br/>Jacorey Palmer<ref name=\"Show\"/>\n| presenter                = [[Cenk Uygur]] {{small|(2002\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Ben Mankiewicz]] {{small|(2002\u20132007; contributor thereafter)}}<br/>[[Jill Pike]] {{small|(2002\u20132007)}}<br/>[[Ana Kasparian]] {{small|(2008\u2013present)}}<br/>[[John Iadarola]] {{small|(2012\u2013present)}}\n| theme_music_composer     = <!--[[APM Music]]-->\n| opentheme                = <!--\"Beatdown\"-->\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| num_seasons              = 16\n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = [[Ana Kasparian]]<br/>\n| location                 = [[Wilshire Boulevard]], California<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=262177544 |title=Company Overview of The Young Turks LLC |website=Bloomberg.com |access-date=October 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232601/https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=262177544 |archive-date=October 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 120 minutes {{small|(main program)}}<br/>Varied {{small|([[post-game show]])}}\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[Sirius Satellite Radio]] {{small|(2002\u20132009, 2009\u20132010, 2017\u2013present)}}<ref>{{cite web |title=TYT Is Now on SiriusXM |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kadM73UmqxA |website=YouTube |access-date=28 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516012853/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kadM73UmqxA |archive-date=May 16, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[Air America (radio network)|Air America]] {{small|(2006\u20132008)}}<br/>[[YouTube]] {{small|(2005\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Roku]] {{small|(2013\u20132016)}}<br/>[[Hulu]] {{small|(2014\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Current TV]] {{small|(2011\u20132013)}}<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news |title='The Young Turks' host Cenk Uygur bets on Web after Current TV |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/15/entertainment/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tronc|Tribune Publishing]] |date=August 15, 2013 |access-date=September 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917134847/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/15/entertainment/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813 |archive-date=September 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[Pluto TV]] {{small|(2014\u2013present)}}<ref>{{cite web |title=We're now on Pluto TV |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2014/04/01/now-pluto-tv/ |website=TYT Network |access-date=16 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807073227/https://tytnetwork.com/2014/04/01/now-pluto-tv/ |archive-date=August 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[YouTube TV]] {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n| picture_format           = '''Television/online:'''<br/>[[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]; 2005\u20132011),<br/>[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]]; 2011\u2013present)\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2002|02|14}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = https://www.tyt.com\n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Young Turks''''' ('''TYT''') is a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/the-young-turks/|title=The Young Turks|website=Media Bias/Fact Check|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] news and opinion show on [[YouTube]] that additionally appears on selected TV channels in the United States. TYT serves as the flagship program of the TYT Network, a [[multi-channel network]] of associated web series focusing on news and current events. TYT covers politics, lifestyle, pop culture, science, sport and other social topics.<ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/><ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\"/> The program was created by [[Cenk Uygur]], [[Ben Mankiewicz]], and Dave Koller. Currently co-hosted by Uygur, [[Ana Kasparian]] and [[John Iadarola]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wme-signs-political-hosts-young-874456|title=WME Signs Political Hosts The Young Turks (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517070736/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wme-signs-political-hosts-young-874456|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> it is also often accompanied by various other in-studio contributors. The program presents an anti-establishment stance and provides commentary on topics of varying news genres. ''The Young Turks'' began as a [[radio program]] that premiered on February 14, 2002, on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]]; it was later carried on [[Air America (radio network)|Air America]], before launching a web series component in 2005 on YouTube. In 2018, Regional News Network offered it initially on [[WMCN-TV|WMCN]], its New Jersey broadcast television station. \n\nIn addition to being carried on the TYT Network and YouTube, it is also currently available on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Direct]], [[iTunes]], [[Hulu]], [[Roku]], on [[Pluto TV]] through a 24-hour feed and on social media platforms [[Instagram]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/><ref name=\"Digital Marketing\"/> It has spawned two [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] [[television series]], one that aired on [[Current TV]]<ref name=\"The Young Turks on Fusuion\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks return to cable TV for election-focused show on Fusion |url=http://mashable.com/2016/05/09/young-turks-fusion-election-show/ |website=Mashable |access-date=17 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208191036/https://mashable.com/2016/05/09/young-turks-fusion-election-show/ |archive-date=December 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> from 2011 to 2013 and a second that debuted on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]] in 2016 as a limited-run program developed to cover the [[2016 United States presidential election]]. ''The Young Turks'' also served as the subject of a documentary, entitled ''[[Mad as Hell]]'', which was released in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madashellfilm.com |title=Mad As Hell |website=Madashellfilm.com |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722225757/http://www.madashellfilm.com/ |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The network also has a linear channel on [[YouTube TV]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Throughout its existence, TYT has relied on small grassroots financial contributions from its viewership to sustain itself as an independent news organisation.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> In 2017, TYT sought to expand its media network and hire more staff through various venture capital fundraising efforts that raised $20-million.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> The growth of the network over the years has made TYT the longest-running and \"largest online news show in the world\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/the-young-turks-celebrates-10th-anniversary-today/|title=The Young Turks Celebrates 10th Anniversary Today|date=2012-02-14|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/><ref name=\"Solaimanxii\"/>\n\n==Format==\n''The Young Turks'' [[Streaming media|live streams]] for up to three hours, with its story selection and associated commentary broken up by format. Issues that the show focuses on include national political news, the [[Campaign finance in the United States|influence of money in the political process]], drug policy, [[social security]], the privatization of public services, [[climate change]], the influence of [[religion]], [[abortion]] and [[reproductive rights]], [[civil and political rights|civil rights]] and issues of injustice towards [[Person of color|people of color]] and [[sexual minority|sexual minorities]], sexual morality, and the influence of [[corporate media|corporations, neutrality and establishment political thought]] on traditional news media. The program maintains a liberal/progressive ideology in its political commentary.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur on the success of The Young Turks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/cenk-uygur-young-turks |first=Chavala |last=Madlena |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian Media, LLC |date=April 26, 2010 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928091053/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/cenk-uygur-young-turks |archive-date=September 28, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Saltonstall>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Glenn Beck's right-wing rants go way too far, critics charge |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/fox-news-glenn-beck-right-wing-rants-critics-charge-article-1.382031 |first=David |last=Saltonstall |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |date=September 12, 2009 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811102010/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/fox-news-glenn-beck-right-wing-rants-critics-charge-article-1.382031 |archive-date=August 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Cenk Uygur Sets Out to Take Down Traditional Television |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/141/young-turks-indeed.html |first=Tina |last=Dupuy |magazine=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |date=December 1, 2009 |access-date=January 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218055722/http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/141/young-turks-indeed.html |archive-date=December 18, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/> Co-creator and host Cenk Uygur describes himself as an \"[[Independent (voter)|independent]] progressive\" and asserts that the show is aimed at the \"98 percent 'not in power'\" and what he describes as the 60 percent of Americans who hold progressive views.<ref name=independent/>\n\nThe first hour, which is occasionally hosted solo by Uygur but frequently has Ana Kasparian among other co-hosts, focuses on [[Politics of the United States|American politics]], foreign policy and [[breaking news]] headlines.<ref>{{cite news |title=On the media: For Young Turk Cenk Uygur, TV is the next frontier |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-onthemedia-20100908,0,435910.column |first=James |last=Rainey |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=September 8, 2010 |access-date=September 9, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009193226/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-onthemedia-20100908,0,435910.column |archive-date=October 9, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second hour \u2013 which is co-hosted by Uygur and Ana Kasparian \u2013 provides social commentary on a wide range of topics, both domestic and foreign. The program also features a [[post-game show]], in which Uygur and Kasparian discuss their personal lives. Uygur has regular bits and on-air interaction with other staff members who create and run the show, including among others Jes\u00fas Godoy, Dave Koller, Jayar Jackson and Steve Oh.\n\nEach Friday, ''The Young Turks'' features a [[panel show|panel]] of guests from the worlds of politics, journalism, pop culture, sports and comedy \u2013 dubbed the \"TYT Power Panel\" \u2013 that is led by Uygur and John Iadarola in the first hour and Kasparian in the second hour. Along with Iadarola, other fill-in hosts and recurring guests include series co-creator/contributor [[Ben Mankiewicz]], comedian [[Jimmy Dore]], television personality [[Brian Unger]], [[Hasan Piker]], Becca Frucht, [[Brett Erlich]], Wes Clark Jr., [[Michael Shure]], [[Cara Santa Maria]], RJ Eskow, Gina Grad, Samantha Schacher, and Jayde Lovell.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Ana Kasparian and Cenk Uygur hosting The Young Turks (26942061744).jpg|thumb|250px|[[Cenk Uygur]] (left) and [[Ana Kasparian]] (right) on the show's set in 2015]]\n''The Young Turks'' is broadcast in a two-to-three hour live stream format, which airs Monday through Fridays at 3:00&nbsp;p.m. Pacific Time. The program was originally based out of the living room of creator/host Cenk Uygur, but it moved production to a small office in [[Los Angeles]] after the show hired a limited staff to produce the program. When the program was given a secondary live show on Current TV in 2011, the network provided a larger studio in Los Angeles to house its television and online broadcasts; production was forced to leave the facility after Current TV was sold to [[Al Jazeera]], prior to the network's conversion into the now-defunct generalized news service [[Al Jazeera America]].\n\nIn 2013, ''The Young Turks{{'}}'' production staff relocated temporarily to new studio quarters at YouTube Space LA in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Digital Marketing\">{{cite web |title=Life after cable: The Young Turks Network launches a Roku app |url=http://www.learn-digital-marketing.com/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |website=Digital Marketing |access-date=July 31, 2013 |quote=The channel's new owners have opted not to keep The Young Turks on the network due to it being political commentary rather than reporting/analysis. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925194401/http://www.learn-digital-marketing.com/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |archive-date=September 25, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2013, ''The Young Turks'' launched an [[Indiegogo]] campaign, aimed at raising $250,000 in order to build a new studio. Fundraising completed with $400,000 being raised.<ref name=\"Indiegog Campaign\">{{cite web |access-date=December 29, 2016 |url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/tyt-let-s-build-it-together-the-young-turks |title=TYT \u2013 Let's Build It Together! The Young Turks |website=Indiegogo |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507004824/https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/tyt-let-s-build-it-together-the-young-turks/ |archive-date=May 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The program moved its production facilities and staff operations to a new studio facilities in Los Angeles later that year, with construction of their new studio being completed in June 2015. In 2017, TYT sought to expand its media network and hire more staff through various venture capital fundraising efforts that raised $20-million.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Radio program===\n''The Young Turks'' was originally developed as a radio [[talk show]] that was similar in format to a Los Angeles-based [[public-access television|public access]] television program that Cenk Uygur had hosted, titled ''The Young Turk''. With the help of friend [[Ben Mankiewicz]] (with whom he had previously worked), his childhood friend Dave Koller, and [[Jill Pike]], Uygur began ''The Young Turks'' as a radio program in February 2002 on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]].<ref name=\"Greenwood96\">{{cite book|last=Greenwood|first=Sue|title=Future Journalism: Where we are and where we're going|year=2017|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317192664|url=https://books.google.com/?id=L4U0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT7#v=onepage&q=TYT%20network&f=false|pages=96|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/><ref name=Guardian/> On the show's website, the title is explained as deriving from the English-language phrase \"Young Turk\", meaning a \"progressive or insurgent member of an institution, movement, or political party\" or a \"young person who rebels against authority or societal expectations\".<ref>{{cite web |title=About. TYT network details |url=http://www.tytnetwork.com/info/ |website=TYT Network |access-date=June 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711124427/http://www.tytnetwork.com/info/ |archive-date=July 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the program received attention for its 99-hour \"Live on Air Filibuster,\" conducted during Congressional hearings for the [[Samuel Alito Supreme Court nomination|nomination]] of [[Samuel Alito]] to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Hosts including [[Thom Hartmann]] and [[Crooks and Liars|John Amato]] filled in during the event, to allow the show's regular hosts and contributors to rest or take breaks.<ref name=\"LAT 2006\">{{cite news |title=Can't get on the network? Get on the Net |url=https://articles.latimes.com/print/2006/mar/19/entertainment/ca-turks19 |first=Matea |last=Gold |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=March 19, 2006 |access-date=July 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127162319/http://articles.latimes.com/print/2006/mar/19/entertainment/ca-turks19 |archive-date=January 27, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to signing a distribution deal to carry the program on [[Air America (radio network)|Air America]] in 2006, the show was broadcast on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]],<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> on Sirius Left 143 and later 146, airing weekdays from 6:00 to 9:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern Time; a day-behind rebroadcast of the program aired on Sirius Talk Central 148 weekday afternoons from 12:00 to 2:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern. Being carried exclusively on Sirius for several years, ''The Young Turks'' was the first show to air exclusively on Sirius Left that was not distributed through a syndication network.{{citation needed|date=September 2010}} TYT was also carried by KFH (1330 AM and 98.7 FM, now [[KNSS (AM)]] and [[KNSS-FM]]) in [[Wichita, Kansas]] each weeknight from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] and [[webcast]] by RadioPower.org.\n\nOn February 2, 2009, TYT was removed from the broadcast schedule of [[America Left]], a progressive talk channel carried on Sirius/XM Channel 167, and replaced by an additional hour of ''[[The Bill Press Show]]''. The program returned to Sirius/XM on March 16, 2009. In late 2010, TYT announced through its [[Facebook]] page that it would discontinue carrying the program on Sirius/XM Satellite Radio; the last edition of ''The Young Turks'' to be carried on the service aired on November 19, 2010. TYT rejoined Sirius/XM in 2017 with the show being run on [[SiriusXM Progress]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165634/the-young-turks-dean-obeidallah-join-siriusxm-prog |title='The Young Turks,' Dean Obeidallah Join SiriusXM Progress Lineup |website=AllAccess.com |date=May 11, 2017 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122005557/https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165634/the-young-turks-dean-obeidallah-join-siriusxm-prog |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Web series===\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align = right\n | width   = 120\n | image1  = Cenk Uygur by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n | alt1  = A man\n | caption1 = \n | image2  = Ana Kasparian (27847150002).jpg\n | caption2 = \n | alt2 = A woman\n | footer = [[Cenk Uygur]] (''top, 2016'') and [[Ana Kasparian]] (''bottom, 2016'') host the web series.\n}}\n''The Young Turks'' was the first daily streaming online talk show, having begun airing in that format in 2006,<ref name=Guardian/> with an official website on the internet and a channel hosted on Youtube.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The show provides in-depth coverage on politics regarding topics, events and other issues.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\"/> \n\nIn August 2007, Ben Mankiewicz left the show to serve as a contributor for [[TMZ (website)|TMZ]]'s syndicated entertainment news program ''[[TMZ on TV]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Young Turks: Ben Mankiewicz Has Left the Building |url=http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2007/8/20/11398/6352/Diary/Ben-Mankiewicz-Has-Left-the-Building |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717044118/http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2007/8/20/11398/6352/Diary/Ben-Mankiewicz-Has-Left-the-Building |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> At roughly the same time, Jill Pike left to pursue a job in [[Washington, D.C.]] [[Ana Kasparian]], then working as an intern for the program, was hired to do pop culture-focused segments. Mankiewicz eventually returned to ''The Young Turks'' as a regular correspondent.\n\nDuring the [[United States elections, 2008|2008 elections]], the show developed close ties to [[Brave New Films]]. The program aired commercials for the independent film production company and featured actors such as [[Robert Greenwald]] and Jonathan Kim as guests.\n\nThe success of TYT is due to a large extent of their shift from radio to the internet through the broadcast of programming content on online platforms.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Uygur and co-host Kasparian applied a populist left branding and programming strategy that made TYT a successful global online organisation, with larger numbers of YouTube subscribers and viewers than several other notable news networks like [[FOX]], [[MSNBC]] and [[CNN]].<ref name=\"Peck105108\">{{cite book|last=Peck|first=Reece|title=Fox populism: Branding conservatism as working class|year=2019|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781108496766|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JFR-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PR9&dq=Fox+Populism:+Branding+Conservatism+as+Working+Class#v=onepage&q=TYT%20uygur&f=false|pages=105, 108|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The presence of TYT on Youtube has given the network a platform to democratise production of content and practices associated with its online distribution through an ability to share, comment and like material on its channel.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Through likes and shares of TYT content on many online platforms, audience members have become a \"virtual word of mouth\" expanding the network's reach to other people with similar views and stimulating the growth of the TYT community.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> \n\nSupport by viewers for alternative media outlets like TYT adopting new technology has meant the network was able to overcome being a small sized organisation of the traditional alternative media landscape.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The emergence of TYT in the digital era has resulted in fewer operational costs regarding organising and communication.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> TYT nonetheless has relied on small grassroots financial contributions from its viewers that gave it the ability to emerge as an alternative media organisation that does not advocate for the interests of corporations.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The financial contributions TYT received went to renting a studio, and to purchase production equipment and furniture.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185186\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|pp=185-186.}}</ref> By 2010, TYT employed people and maintained a budget resembling the size of a small newspaper.<ref name=\"May506\"/> \n\nOn July 30, 2013, ''The Young Turks'' launched a TYT Network [[mobile app|app]] on Roku,<ref>{{cite web |title=Life after cable: The Young Turks Network launches a Roku app |url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/07/30/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |website=VentureBeat |date=July 30, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804064136/http://venturebeat.com/2013/07/30/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |archive-date=August 4, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> which features much of the same content that is already available for free through the program's YouTube channel,<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=185.}}</ref> which has over 4.2&nbsp;million subscribers and generates 50 million monthly views. The network is among the few online channels to generate more than 1&nbsp;billion views since launching on YouTube, which does not market a channel on the Roku app store. Young Turks COO Steve Oh acknowledged that making the TYT Network available on Roku was the first part of a strategy to continue the network's growth, regardless of what medium in which its viewers are watching its content, with the intent to figure out a way to monetize its programming through multiple distribution channels, rather than relying on one or two larger channels (such as YouTube or cable television distribution). The network also announced plans to unveil native apps for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. Oh also noted that the network's representatives were speaking with other media platforms about expanding its programming.\n\nIn April 2014, ''The Young Turks'' began offering its content on [[Hulu]]. With this, it began providing a condensed 30-minute version of the program featuring excerpts from the full two-hour daily show, along with a 30-minute weekly version of its daily pop-culture show ''PopTrigger'', with other shows being added shortly afterward. Oh stated on the Hulu launch that, \"as TYT Network has grown from a single show to an entire network, we've consistently found ways to bring our shows to more people[..] We've long admired Hulu as a leader of online video and both parties saw an opportunity to bring digitally-native politics and pop culture talk shows to Hulu's audience.\" He also stated that the company is pitching shows to cable network, but had no immediate plans to revive a television broadcast as either a relaunched program or a show similar in format to the one it formerly produced for Current TV.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur's Young Turks Network launches shows on Hulu |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-the-young-turks-network-launches-shows-on-hulu-20140321-story.html |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=March 24, 2014 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315035048/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-the-young-turks-network-launches-shows-on-hulu-20140321-story.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe website's yearly revenue was roughly US$3&nbsp;million in 2013. According to Cenk Uygur, \"about a third of the revenue comes from subscriptions, and the rest comes from YouTube ads.\" At that time, the company maintained a staff of 30 employees.<ref name=faughnder /> In 2014, the company received a US$4&nbsp;million investment from Roemer, Robinson, Melville & Co., LLC, a [[private equity firm]] led by Republican former Louisiana Governor [[Buddy Roemer]].<ref>{{cite news |title=YouTube Network The Young Turks Raises $4 Million To Expand To New Platforms |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/04/16/the-young-turks-4m/ |last1=Lawler |first1=Ryan |website=[[TechCrunch]] |date=16 April 2014 |access-date=January 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408000647/http://techcrunch.com/2014/04/16/the-young-turks-4m/ |archive-date=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2016, TYT Network launched a crowdfunding campaign aiming to raise [[United States dollar|US$]]2&nbsp;million for the hiring of four further investigative teams.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Young Turks Raising $2 Million To Fund Four Investigative Teams |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/12/09/the-young-turks-fundraising-investigative-journalism |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=December 9, 2016 |access-date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112700/http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/12/09/the-young-turks-fundraising-investigative-journalism/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Five months later, the aim was met.<ref>{{cite web |title=TYT Reaches $2 Million in Fundraising Campaign |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2017/05/18/tyt-reaches-2-million-in-fundraising-campaign |website=The Young Turks |access-date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107222226/https://tytnetwork.com/2017/05/18/tyt-reaches-2-million-in-fundraising-campaign/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2017, it was announced that The Young Turks have raised $20&nbsp;million in venture-capital from 3L Capital, WndrCo (owned by businessman [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]]),<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/young-turks-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco-funding-1202518938/|title=Jeffrey Katzenberg's WndrCo Invests in TYT Network as Part of $20 Million Round|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 8, 2017|access-date=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423153740/https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/young-turks-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco-funding-1202518938/|archive-date=April 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=The Young Turks Raises $20 Million From Jeffrey Katzenberg's WndrCo, Greycroft, 3L Capital, More |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/08/08/the-young-turks-20-million-funding-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco/ |website=TubeFilter |date=August 8, 2017 |access-date=Oct 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107024123/http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/08/08/the-young-turks-20-million-funding-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last1=Tani |first1=Maxwell |title=Progressive media outlet The Young Turks has raised $20&nbsp;million in venture-capital funding and plans to double its staff |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/young-turks-fundraising-venture-capital-criticism-2017-8 |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=31 October 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813142351/https://www.businessinsider.com/young-turks-fundraising-venture-capital-criticism-2017-8 |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Greycroft]], and [[e.ventures]]. TYT stated it would use the funds to \"hire additional management execs and creative talent, as well as enhance its subscription-video offering and expand marketing initiatives\". Shawn Colo, managing partner of 3L Capital, joined the TYT Network's board.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nTYT operates under a strategy of diversifying its finances that involves the airing of socially responsible advertisements, offering subscriptions for TYT membership, selling its own merchandise and other investments.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>  Among its advertising partners is Aspiration Bank, an organisation involved in \"socially conscious and sustainable banking services\" and whom TYT presents as different from other banks and their fossil fuel and campaign financing investments.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Due to popular demand from viewers, TYT established an online outlet selling its own label branded merchandise, such as t-shirts, that are often designed and voted upon through the input of its audience.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Its online subscription membership has two plans, \"insider\" offering full web content access and discounts, and \"activist\", offering additional access to its townhalls and political events.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> \n\nFollowing the 2016 election, TYT fundraised for small grassroots donations among its members, raising thousands of dollars and created a media division named ''TYT Investigates'' devoted to investigative journalism with the aim to hold people with power to account.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> Operating as a watchdog outfit, ''TYT Investigates'' through its investigative journalistic team reports on issues such as inequalities in the economic system, power held by corporations, and other topics sidelined by traditional media like the views of ordinary citizens at political events.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> For example, TYT journalist Emma Vigland has attended US President [[Donald Trump]]'s political rallies and interviewed supporters.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> \n\nIn November 2017, TYT fired field reporter [[Jordan Chariton]] over [[Weinstein effect|sexual assault allegations]] made against him by the Huffington Post.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/11/20/young-turks-and-reporter-abruptly-part-ways-following-sexual-assault-allegations/ |title=The Young Turks and Reporter Abruptly Part Ways Following Sexual Assault Allegations |last=Ch\u00e1vez |first=A\u00edda |date=21 November 2017 |website=[[The Intercept]] |language=en-US |access-date=22 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121011705/https://theintercept.com/2017/11/20/young-turks-and-reporter-abruptly-part-ways-following-sexual-assault-allegations/ |archive-date=November 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Lima\"/> Chariton denied the accusations, considered legal actions<ref name=\"Lima\">{{cite news|last=Lima|first=Cristiano|title=Ousted 'Young Turks' reporter files $23.5 million suit against HuffPost|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/13/young-turks-huffington-post-295474|agency=Politico|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=28 February 2020||url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and later he settled the matter with TYT.<ref name=\"Flood\">{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Brian|title=Liberal HuffPost scraps contributor network amid 'tsunami of false information'|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/liberal-huffpost-scraps-contributor-network-amid-tsunami-of-false-information|agency=FOX News|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=28 February 2020|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-December 2017, Politico reported that TYT was courting former [[CBS Evening News]] anchor [[Dan Rather]] to host a news show.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calderone |first1=Michael |url=https://www.politico.com/media/newsletters/morning-media/2017/12/13/alabama-shocker-the-post-and-the-times-how-hannity-undermines-mueller-acostas-access-threatened-001400 |title=Alabama shocker \u2014 'The Post' and The Times \u2014 Hannity undermines Mueller \u2014 'Forged' Schumer doc shopped \u2014 Acosta's access threatened |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=22 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012121907/https://www.politico.com/media/newsletters/morning-media/2017/12/13/alabama-shocker-the-post-and-the-times-how-hannity-undermines-mueller-acostas-access-threatened-001400 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 21, 2018, TYT confirmed that it will show ''The News with Dan Rather'', a half-hour \"untraditional evening newscast\" weekly on Mondays in the time slot before the main Young Turks show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/21/media/dan-rather-the-young-turks/index.html |title=Dan Rather launching weekly show with progressive outlet The Young Turks Network |last=Darcy |first=Oliver |work=CNN Money |access-date=22 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205220923/https://money.cnn.com/2018/01/21/media/dan-rather-the-young-turks/index.html |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2020, the [[International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees]] (IATSE) sought to unionise the production and post-production staff at TYT.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2020/02/iatse-launches-drive-to-unionize-the-young-turks-news-site-1202858884/ IATSE Launches Drive To Unionize The Young Turks News Site] By David Robb, Labor Editor, www.deadline.com, February 12, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.iatse.net/news/employees-young-turks-announce-unionization EMPLOYEES AT THE YOUNG TURKS ANNOUNCE UNIONIZATION] www.iatse.net, Tuesday, February, 18, 2020.</ref> Uygur urged his employees not to, as he stated TYT is a small media organisation and the move would endanger its financial viability, however the network has supported its workers holding a secret ballot to unionise.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\"/><ref name=\"Floodun\"/> Employees have expressed support for an open ballot and the bargaining process is ongoing.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\"/><ref name=\"Floodun\">{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Brian|title=Young Turks founder Cenk Uygur says a union would hurt progressive outlet|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/young-turks-union-cenk-uygur|agency=FOX News|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Linear channel===\nOn May 17, 2018, The Young Turks launched a 24-hour linear channel on [[YouTube TV]] which includes all of TYT's current shows and four new shows called ''The Damage Report'', ''\"#NoFilter\"'',''\"The Happy Half Hour\"'' and ''\"Old-School Sports\"''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/youtube-tv-tastemade-young-turks-linear-channels-1202812759/ |title=YouTube TV Launches Tastemade, TYT Network 24-Hour Linear Channels |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=2018-05-17 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=2018-05-18 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828212710/https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/youtube-tv-tastemade-young-turks-linear-channels-1202812759/ |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The channel has since been made available on The Roku Channel, Pluto TV, and Xumo as well.\n\n==Reception==\n* In September 2018, the company launched a membership drive, reporting the number of members to be around 27,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peterson |first1=Tim |title=The Young Turks now has 27k paying subscribers accounting for half of its revenue |url=https://digiday.com/media/young-turks-now-27k-paying-subscribers-accounting-half-revenue/ |access-date=10 September 2018 |website=[[DigiDay]] |date=29 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921122009/https://digiday.com/media/young-turks-now-27k-paying-subscribers-accounting-half-revenue/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* As of August 2018, TYT had approximately 27,000 paying subscribers online.<ref name=faughnder/>\n* As of September 2017, the program's [[YouTube]] channel averages a daily hit count of 2 million views per day.<ref>{{cite web |title=YouTube Top 100 Most Viewed News &amp; Politics Video Producers |url=http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-viewed-news-politics |website=Vidstatsx.com |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407202320/http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-viewed-news-politics |archive-date=April 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* By August 2016, Cenk Uygur reported that number of paid subscribers had increased to more than 23,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2016/08/22/how-can-you-create-the-most-progressive-show-on-the-planet/ |title=How You Can Create The Most Progressive Show on the Planet |website=The Young Turks |via=YouTube |access-date=April 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823173153/https://tytnetwork.com/2016/08/22/how-can-you-create-the-most-progressive-show-on-the-planet/ |archive-date=August 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* By October 2016, the total number of views for the TYT Network's YouTube channel had surpassed 3&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"3billion\">{{cite av media |title=TYT Network About Section |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TheYoungTurks/about |publisher=TYT Network |via=YouTube |date=November 17, 2017 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230173811/https://www.youtube.com/user/TheYoungTurks/about |archive-date=December 30, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On April 20, 2013, ''The Young Turks'' announced that its YouTube channel had received over 1&nbsp;billion video views.<ref name=\"The Young Turks Hits 1 Billion Views!\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks Hits 1 Billion Views! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tJ7ei0a1ZZE |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |access-date=April 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016203359/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tJ7ei0a1ZZE |archive-date=October 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2006 article, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' contributing writer Paul Bedard described TYT as \"the loudly liberal counter to the right-leaning presets on my Sirius Satellite Radio.\"<ref name=USNews>{{cite magazine |title=Air America's young turks |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/paulyblog/2006/09/air_americas_young_turks.htm |first=Paul |last=Bedard |magazine=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=September 13, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113202025/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/paulyblog/2006/09/air_americas_young_turks.htm |archivedate=January 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[The Independent]]'' described it as \"the most-watched online news show in the world.\"<ref name=independent>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur's The Young Turks: This YouTube news bulletin is challenging the fogeys of US TV |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/opinion/cenk-uygurs-the-young-turks-this-youtube-news-bulletin-is-challenging-the-fogeys-of-us-tv-9761069.html |first=Ian |last=Burrell |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=September 28, 2014 |access-date=January 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108211629/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/opinion/cenk-uygurs-the-young-turks-this-youtube-news-bulletin-is-challenging-the-fogeys-of-us-tv-9761069.html |archive-date=January 8, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe network is reliant on its multimedia platforms to attract online viewers and its audience are either \"young, educated, affluent and politically interested\" people who consume news from online sources.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> As a result of ongoing TYT membership drives, its base of subscribed members has grown numbering 32,000 in 2019.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Over 12 million viewers (2019) are subscribed to its multiple online channels.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> TYT has become one of the largest watched online networks with its videos seen over 8 billion times (2019).<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> TYT's [[Millennials|millennial]] viewership ranks the network first for news and politics across its online platforms.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>  \n\n===Awards and nominations===\n''The Young Turks'' has won and been nominated for numerous Internet content awards, including, but not limited to: \n\n* In 2009, the program won in the Political category at the [[Podcast Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |title=2009 Podcast Awards Winners |url=http://www.podcastconnect.com/2009/12/2009-podcast-awards-winners/ |first=Todd |last=Cochrane |website=[[Podcast Awards]] |date=December 12, 2009 |access-date=December 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216071508/http://www.podcastconnect.com/2009/12/2009-podcast-awards-winners/ |archive-date=December 16, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won for \"Best Political News Site\" at the [[Mashable#Mashable Awards|Mashable Open Web Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Open Web Awards 2009: The Winners |url=http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/ |first=Pete |last=Cashmore |website=[[Mashable]] |date=December 16, 2009 |access-date=January 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301163609/http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/ |archive-date=March 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In [[2nd Streamy Awards|2010]], it was nominated for a [[Streamy Awards|Streamy Award]] for \"Best News or Political Web Series\" and the \"Audience Choice Award for Best Web Series\".<ref>{{cite web |title=2nd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/2010-nominees/ |website=[[Streamy Awards]] |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508013524/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/2010-nominees/ |archive-date=May 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2011, the program won in the News category at the [[Shorty Awards#Third Annual Shorty Awards|Third Annual]] [[Shorty Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |title=3rd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://3rd.shortyawards.com/ |website=[[Shorty Awards]] |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504223654/http://3rd.shortyawards.com/ |archive-date=May 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won for \"Best News and Political Series\" at [[2011 Webby Awards|that year's]] [[Webby Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=15th Annual Webby Awards Nominees & Winners |url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?media_id=97&season=15#film_news_series |website=[[Webby Award]]s |access-date=June 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5xvYAKEsL?url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?media_id=97&season=15#film_news_series |archive-date=April 14, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2012, it won in the Best Video Podcast category at the [[Podcast Awards]] .<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |title=Podcast Award Winners 2005-2014 |access-date=May 15, 2016 |website=[[Podcast Awards]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Lh9tnIpR?url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |archive-date=December 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In [[3rd Streamy Awards|2013]], the program was nominated for two Streamy Awards in the Best News and Culture Series and Audience Choice Award for Series of the Year categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=3rd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/3rd-annual-nominees/ |website=Streamy Awards |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301233651/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/3rd-annual-nominees/ |archive-date=March 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2015, ''The Young Turks'' also won a Streamy Award in the News and Culture category.<ref>{{cite web |title=5th Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/5th-annual-nominees-winners/ |website=Streamy Awards |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816150658/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/5th-annual-nominees-winners/ |archive-date=August 16, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2017, TYT won the Shorty Awards Audience Honor for the Best in Overall YouTube Presence.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>\n\nOther awards won by ''The Young Turks'' in the 2010s were \"Best Political News Site\" and the  \"People's Voice Webby Award\" in all 5 of its categories.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>\n\n==Television spin-offs==\n\n===''The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur''===\nThe first linear television incarnation of the program began as an hour-long show that premiered on [[Current TV]] on December 5, 2011. Co-created and hosted by Cenk Uygur (who executive produced the series with original program co-creator Dave Koller, with Jesus Godoy, Jayar Jackson and Mark Register serving as producers), the program was co-presented by Ana Kasparian, with Ben Mankiewicz, Michael Shure, Brian Unger, Wes Clark Jr. and RJ Eskow as contributors and correspondents. It was filmed at studio facilities in the [[Los Angeles]] suburb of [[Culver City, California|Culver City]].\n\nCurrent TV announced the launch of a separate television broadcast of ''The Young Turks'' on September 20, 2011, with the program intending to air Monday through Friday evenings at 7:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern Time beginning in the fourth quarter of 2011. It was the second news and opinion program to air on Current, alongside ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'', and was part of a strategy to refocus the network's prime time schedule around progressive talk programming (which was followed by the debut of ''[[The War Room with Jennifer Granholm]]'' in January 2012). According to the show's website, the show was titled ''The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur'' to differentiate itself from the popular web series.<ref name=\"CurrTV\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur |url=http://current.com/shows/the-young-turks/ |website=Current TV |access-date=August 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807205849/http://current.com/shows/the-young-turks/ |archive-date=August 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> For two years, the two separate shows were produced each Monday through Thursday, with a one-hour break between the production airtimes of the television and web shows. In a press release, representatives for Current described TYT as \"a group of progressive, outspoken journalists and commentators discussing politics and pop culture\" and founder Cenk Uygur as bringing a, \"uniquely progressive and topical commentary about politics and pop culture.\"<ref name=\"CurrTV\"/>\n\nOn January 2, 2013, Current TV was sold to Qatar-owned broadcaster [[Al Jazeera Media Network]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Al Jazeera targets US expansion after buying Current TV |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20896484 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=January 3, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820225517/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20896484 |archive-date=August 20, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> which announced plans to reorganize the channel as [[Al Jazeera America]], focusing on world news and investigative content with a more neutral tone; with the move, the channel would discontinue its talk programming slate, including ''The Young Turks with Cenk Ugyur'', which ended its run on Current TV on August 15, 2013, shortly before the network's relaunch.<ref name=faughnder/><ref>{{cite web |title=TYT is Independent, Not Owned by Current or Al Jazeera |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yfJcyDmZHu0 |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |date=January 3, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118210329/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yfJcyDmZHu0 |archive-date=January 18, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]],'' Uygur commented that with the discontinuance of the television broadcast, he was relieved to move on and focus on his web show and the TYT Network site, stating that he had been \"exhausted from doing the two shows at once\" and that he was glad to put his energies there, as he believes that the future of media will gravitate towards online content. Uygur also noted that he talked with Al Jazeera after the company bought Current, reaching a mutual agreement not to continue with the television broadcast due to the change in ideological tone that Al Jazeera America would maintain.<ref name=faughnder>{{cite news |title='The Young Turks' host Cenk Uygur bets on Web after Current TV |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813,0,7754856.story |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=August 12, 2013 |access-date=August 17, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816040307/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813,0,7754856.story |archive-date=August 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, members of ''The Young Turks{{'}}'' on-air contributing staff, such as [[Michael Shure]] (who served as a political and general assignment contributor), [[Cara Santa Maria]] (part of [[TechKnow]]) and [[Ben Mankiewicz]] (who worked as a movie critic), regularly appeared on Al Jazeera America. ''The Young Turks'' also maintain a partnership with Al Jazeera's digital channel [[AJ+]], in an arrangement first announced in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Exciting New Partnership! Check Out AJ+ |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XYC1IpG-8bg |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |date=March 20, 2015 |accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===''The Young Turks on Fusion''===\n''The Young Turks'' returned to television with a weekly, hour-long program on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]], ''The Young Turks on Fusion'', which premiered on September 12, 2016 for a twelve-week limited run. Hosted by Ana Kasparian and John Iadarola, the program \u2013 which was broadcast from college campuses around the United States, in a live-audience format modelled after [[ESPN]]'s ''[[College GameDay (football)|College GameDay]]'' \u2013 focused on coverage of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 United States presidential campaign]]. The show also featured Cenk Uygur, Jimmy Dore, Ben Mankiewicz, Hannah Cranston, [[Hasan Piker]], and Kim Horcher as contributors, as well as Fusion reporters and celebrity guest hosts.<ref>{{cite magazine |title='Young Turks' Will Get 12-Week Run on Fusion |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/young-turks-fusion-1201769078/ |first=Brian |last=Steinberg |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 9, 2016 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512005342/http://variety.com/2016/tv/news/young-turks-fusion-1201769078/ |archive-date=May 12, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fusion to Model Young Turks Show on ESPN's 'College Game Day' |url=https://thewrap.com/young-turks-fusion-espn-college-game-day/ |author=Brian Flood |website=[[The Wrap]] |publisher=The Wrap Media, LLC |date=May 9, 2016 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514060750/http://www.thewrap.com/young-turks-fusion-espn-college-game-day/ |archive-date=May 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==TYT Network==\n''The Young Turks'' has spawned a [[multi-channel network]] of associated web series and shows, known as the TYT Network.\n\nSome of the programs produced for the service are produced in-house, among which include:\n* ''Aggressive Progressives'' \u2013 a weekly political talk and satire show that debuted in August 2016; it is co-hosted by Ron Placone, [[Graham Elwood]], and Steve Oh. It was co-hosted by [[Jimmy Dore]] from August 2016 until Dore's departure from the TYT Network in April 2019. It is streamed each Thursday to TYT Network members, with select segments being made available to all viewers each Saturday on ''The Young Turks''{{'}}s official YouTube channel.\n* ''TYT Sports'' \u2013 a sports commentary program that debuted in 2011; originally hosted by Cenk Uygur, Jayar Jackson and Ben Mankiewicz, Rick Strom took over as co-host in 2013 and was replaced in 2014 by Jason Rubin and Francis Maxwell.\n* \u2018\u2019Old School\u2019\u2019 - a more laid-back show hosted by Cenk Uygur and Ben Mankiewicz discussing every-day topics and telling stories \n* ''Styleogue'' \u2013 a fashion and lifestyle program that debuted in 2014, which is dedicated to affordable fashion.\n* ''Rebel HQ'' \u2013 an \"on-the-road\" political commentary and interview program formerly<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/jordan-chariton-young-turks-lawsuit-firing-259363 |title='Young Turks' reporter vows to sue over his firing |first=Cristiano |last=Lima |date=22 November 2017 |website=Politico |access-date=27 November 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123010218/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/jordan-chariton-young-turks-lawsuit-firing-259363 |archive-date=November 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> hosted by reporter [[Jordan Chariton]], which was created to cover the 2016 United States presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Reporter Jumps to The Young Turks |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/jordan-chariton-wrap-young-turks/362758 |first=Richard |last=Horgan |website=[[Adweek]] |date=December 20, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420030001/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/jordan-chariton-wrap-young-turks/362758 |archive-date=April 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Young Turks Pushes More Political Coverage, Adds Jordan Chariton To Team |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/12/21/the-young-turks-jordan-chariton-2016-election/ |first=Bree |last=Brouwer |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=December 21, 2015 |access-date=April 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331204552/http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/12/21/the-young-turks-jordan-chariton-2016-election/ |archive-date=March 31, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The channel is now primarily hosted by Emma Vigeland and with other segments and interviews hosted by Cenk Uygur and Mark Thompson. Formerly ''TYT Politics''\n* ''TYT Interviews'' \u2013 an interview series conducted by Cenk Uygur, and occasionally by other hosts.\n* ''TYT Investigates'' \u2013 the investigative reporting division of The Young Turks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tytnetwork.com/investigates/|title=TYT Investigates|website=TYT Network.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903154757/https://tytnetwork.com/investigates/|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> hosted by Michael Tracey, [[Ryan Grim]], David Sirota, Eric Byler, Dylan Ratigan, Ken Klippenstein, and other reporters.\n* ''The Damage Report'' \u2013 morning show hosted by John Iadarola focused the most critical issues facing the U.S. today\n* ''#NoFilter'' \u2013 analysis and commentary from TYT host Ana Kasparian\n* ''The Happy Half Hour'' \u2013 hosted by Brett Erlich, it's a more upbeat and lighter look at the \"not bad\" news of the week\n* ''Old-School Sports'' \u2013 TYT Sports host Rick Strom & BlackSportsOnline Owner Robert Littal revisits and analyzes classic games and rivalries.\n* ''Murder with Friends'' - Grace Baldridge invites guests to talk about some of history's most notorious murderers.\n\nOther shows are not produced in-house:\n* ''[[The Majority Report]]'' \u2013 a news and politics show hosted by [[Sam Seder]], which is a video broadcast of Seder's daily online radio program.\n* ''[[Richard A. Fowler#The Richard Fowler Show|The Richard Fowler Show]]'' \u2013 a weekly political talk show hosted by [[Richard A. Fowler]].\n* ''Secular Talk'' \u2013 a daily political talk show hosted by Kyle Kulinski, which is also broadcast on the Secular Talk Radio and [[BlogTalkRadio]] online networks.\n* ''The Humanist Report'' \u2013 a progressive political YouTube channel and podcast hosted by political scientist Mike Figueredo that began in 2015.\n* ''[[The Bill Press Show]]'' \u2013 a daily talk show hosted by [[Bill Press]], which is broadcast online, over radio and on [[Free Speech TV]] that became affiliated with the TYT Network in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2016/11/22/bill-press-show-joins-as-tyt-network-partner/ |title=Bill Press Show Joins as TYT Network Partner |date=November 22, 2016 |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020611/https://tytnetwork.com/2016/11/22/bill-press-show-joins-as-tyt-network-partner/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Acronym TV \u2013 a commentary program focusing on policy and national security issues, hosted by Dennis Trainor Jr.\n* ''Absurdity Today'' \u2013 a news satire program, hosted by Juliana Forlano.\n* ''The Undercurrent'' \u2013 a talk program hosted by Lauren Windsor, which covers a broad variety of in-depth topics, and includes interviews with politicians, media figures and opinion makers, as well as documentaries.\n* ''The Lip TV'' \u2013 a commentary program which maintains a live and unscripted format with a panel of experts on varying subjects of focus.\n* ''Truth Mashup'' \u2013 a weekly [[Canada|Canadian]] comedy show, co-hosted by Bree Essrig (who formerly co-hosted ''Pop Trigger'') and comedian and media activist Ron Placone.\n* ''ScIQ'' \u2013 a bi-weekly infotainment series hosted by Jayde Lovell, an Australian-born [[neurophysiologist]] and director of science PR consulting firm ReAgency, which explores scientific topics.\n* ''Around the Nation with Jeff Waldorf'' aka ''TYT Nation'' \u2013 a talk show hosted by Jeff Waldorf.\n\nPrograms produced for the TYT Network that are no longer in production include:\n* ''thetopvlog'' \u2013 a series of [[vlog]]s by [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] political commentators that TYT helped launch in June 2010.\n* ''twenTYTwelve'' \u2013 a political interview and commentary program, hosted by [[Michael Shure]], that was launched in October 2011 to cover the [[United States elections, 2012|2012 United States elections]].\n* ''TYT Now'' \u2013 a commentary program that was hosted by columnist [[Tina Dupuy]] and Tim Mihalsky, which ran from May to August 2011.\n* ''WMB'' \u2013 a commentary program hosted by Ben Mankiewicz, Michael Shure and Wes Clark Jr., which ran from May to June 2011.\n* ''Reality Bites Back'' \u2013 a [[reality television]]-focused review series, hosted by Jacki Bray and Misty Kingma, which ran from May to July 2011.\n* ''ThinkTank'' \u2013 a science and social commentary program that originated in 2011 as ''TYT University'', before relaunching under its current format in 2014; hosted by Hannah Cranston alongside a rotation of guest co-hosts (including original co-host John Iadarola, who diminished his role on ''ThinkTank'' during 2017), the program deals with new facts, discoveries and perspectives on the world and people.<ref>{{cite web |title=YouTube Millionaires: For ThinkTank's John Iadarola, A Re-Brand Led To Success |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/03/17/youtube-millionaires-think-tank-john-iadarola/ |first=Sam |last=Gutelle |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=March 17, 2016 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703132844/http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/03/17/youtube-millionaires-think-tank-john-iadarola/ |archive-date=July 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The Point'' \u2013 a [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] [[panel show]], hosted by Ana Kasparian, that debuted in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |title=30 Under 30 2016: Media |url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/media/ |first1=Emily |last1=Inverso |first2=Glynnis |last2=MacNicol |website=[[Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes, LLC |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612080916/http://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/media/ |archive-date=June 12, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ana Kasparian From 'The Young Turks' Says Her Feminism Means Wearing Heels Whenever The Hell She Wants |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/124162-ana-kasparian-from-the-young-turks-says-her-feminism-means-wearing-heels-whenever-the-hell-she |first=Josephine |last=Yurcaba |magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=November 17, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618032203/http://www.bustle.com/articles/124162-ana-kasparian-from-the-young-turks-says-her-feminism-means-wearing-heels-whenever-the-hell-she |archive-date=June 18, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> but has been on hiatus since January, 2016.\n* ''Pop Trigger'' \u2013 an [[infotainment]] show, hosted by [[Brett Erlich]] and Grace Baldridge with a rotating slate of guest co-hosts, that provides intelligent conversation on pop culture news. Ran until August. 2018.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)-->\n* ''Nerd Alert'' \u2013 a show that focuses on news about technology, gaming, movies and online geek culture; hosted by Kim Horcher, the program [[Spin-off (media)|spun off]] from a segment that originated on ''TYT University''. Ran until August, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Young Turks' Kim Horcher joins #TalkingTechLive panel |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/08/15/young-turks-kim-horcher-joins-talkingtechlive-panel/31797695/ |first=Jefferson |last=Graham |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=August 15, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150256/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/08/15/young-turks-kim-horcher-joins-talkingtechlive-panel/31797695/ |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The News with Dan Rather'' \u2013 A weekly 30-minute rundown of current events with commentary hosted by ex-CBS News lead anchor [[Dan Rather]]. Filmed in Dan Rather's personal office in New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Premieres Monday: The News with Dan Rather |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2018/01/21/premieres-monday-the-news-with-dan-rather |author=julietyt |website=[[TYT Network]] |date=January 21, 2018 |access-date=January 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124073047/https://tytnetwork.com/2018/01/21/premieres-monday-the-news-with-dan-rather/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''What the Flick?!'' \u2013 a [[film criticism|film review]] series that began in 2010; it is hosted by Ben Mankiewicz, [[Christy Lemire]], Matt Atchity and [[Alonso Duralde]].<ref name=Guardian/> Guest critics have included Robert Abele, William Bibbiani, Grae Drake, Tim Grierson, Amy Nicholson, Witney Seibold, Dave White, and April Wolfe. Ran until August, 2018.\n\nPrograms no longer produced or owned by the TYT Network, but are still in production:\n* ''[[The Rubin Report]]'' (broke away in August 2015) \u2013 a political news [[talk show]], hosted by [[Dave Rubin]], that premiered in 2013; the program moved to [[RYOT News]] in 2015, and later to [[Ora TV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report-young-turks-_n_2786849.html |title=Dave Rubin, Gay Radio Host And Comedian, Launches 'The Rubin Report' Panel Show |date=February 2, 2016 |website=[[HuffPost]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |first=Curtis |last=Wong |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810085026/http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report-young-turks-_n_2786849.html |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report_us_55b93fb5e4b095423d0dbad5 |title=Comedian And LGBT Advocate Dave Rubin Brings 'The Rubin Report' To Ora TV |date=July 31, 2015 |website=HuffPost |publisher=AOL |first=Curtis |last=Wong |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810092511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report_us_55b93fb5e4b095423d0dbad5 |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''[[The David Pakman Show]]'' \u2013 a political and current events radio show, hosted by [[David Pakman]], that began in 2005 and was affiliated with the TYT Network from 2012 to 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=David Pakman Joins The Young Turks Network |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/david-pakman-show-young-turks-cenk-uygur-ana-kasperian/172862 |first=Richard |last=Horgan |website=Adweek |date=May 31, 2012 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402102556/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/david-pakman-show-young-turks-cenk-uygur-ana-kasperian/172862 |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The Jimmy Dore Show'' \u2013 a commentary program hosted by stand-up comedian and political commentator [[Jimmy Dore]] that began in 2009 and was affiliated with the TYT Network from 2009 to 2019.\n\n== Political activity ==\nTYT promotes itself as the \"Home of Progressives\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Uygur has stated that \"TYT values journalistic objectivity\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> TYT commentary generates \"hybridized content\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> This involves TYT referencing news from mainstream sources and providing its own content analysis by connecting it to different narratives and discourses related to the social realities of its audience.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> The network's commentary has generated counter narratives in relation to traditional policy discussions.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> TYT places news in its context and connects it to the decision making process.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=192.}}</ref> By engaging with social movements, the station has called on its audience to became part of its \"TYT army\".<ref name=\"May506\">{{cite journal|last=May|first=Albert L.|title=Who tube? How YouTube's news and politics space is going mainstream|journal=The International Journal of Press/Politics|volume=15|issue=4|year=2010|pages=506|ref=harv|doi=10.1177/1940161210382861|citeseerx=10.1.1.1027.3801}}</ref> The network uses its platforms for advocacy, such as calling for its audience to participate in the political process and give candidates support.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> \n\nAs part of new media, TYT coverage conveys the frustration and discontent held by youth with the political system.<ref name=\"Solaimanxii\"/> Progressive social policies and liberal values are promoted through commentary by TYT.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Examples include TYT calling for [[Gun politics in the United States|gun control]] and the need to mitigate [[Police brutality in the United States|violence by police]] during its coverage of the 2018 [[Parkland school shooting]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> In similar coverage of [[Mass shootings in the United States|shootings]], TYT has provided information on [[Gun violence in the United States|gun and crime related homicide numbers]] and placed into context the [[Gun law in the United States|laws]], police training and additional factors that worsen the situation.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Hosts on TYT advocate for unionisation in large companies and the sharing of profits with their workers.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\">[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-young-turks-progressive-founder-urged-his-staff-not-to-unionize_n_5e540686c5b6ad3de3823a32 The Young Turks\u2019 Progressive Founder Urged His Staff Not To Unionize] By Dave Jamieson, The Huffington Post, February 24, 2020.</ref>  The network has spoken out against corruption in politics and for the need to remove corporate donations out of the political system.<ref name=\"Solaimanxii\">{{cite thesis|last=Solaiman|first=Barry|date=2017|title=Evaluating Lobbying in the United Kingdom: Moving from a Corruption Framework to 'Institutional Diversion'|type=Ph.D.|publisher=University of Cambridge|url=https://www.repository.cam.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/1810/269394/Solaiman-2017-PhD.pdf?sequence=1|access-date=24 February 2020|pages=xii|ref=harv}}</ref> The station has been critical of what it regards as a \"corporate coup\" in the US.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> TYT has criticised politicians from the US [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] for alleged attachment to financial interests and for appearing to be progressive.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> Hosts on TYT have called for the Democratic Party to undergo a revitalisation process.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The network has been critical of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] (TPP) trade deal and its supporters like Hillary Clinton, whereas TYT approved of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]' opposition to it.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The station has defended the [[whistleblower]] [[WikiLeaks]] organisation and its data disclosures on several issues such as the TPP, the [[DNC email leak]] and the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref name=\"Marmura87100115\">{{harvnb|Marmura|2018|pp=87, 100, 115.}}</ref> TYT was sceptical about claims of alleged [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 US presidential election]].<ref name=\"Marmura115123\">{{cite book|last=Marmura|first=Stephen M. E.|title=The WikiLeaks Paradigm: Paradoxes and Revelations|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319971391|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iE1tDwAAQBAJ&pg=PP5&dq=The+WikiLeaks+Paradigm:+Paradoxes+and+Revelations#v=onepage&q=TYT&f=false|pages=115, 123|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe station uses traditional and online media platforms regarding political action and mobilisation for citizen engagement with institutional politics.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/><ref name=\"Marmura100\">{{harvnb|Marmura|2018|p=100.}}</ref> For example, TYT townhalls are hosted in local communities involving a moderator asking questions of the expert panel followed by audience questions, with the events streamed on Youtube and on-demand web access for its subscription membership.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=186}}</ref> Viewers also have the option to send video questions to the network if they are unable to be present at the townhall.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> TYT townhall events involve detailed commentary by hosts and guests on political topics ranging from personal experiences to abstract notions on issues of concern that serve to connect their audience and lived experiences with politics.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> During the 2016 US presidential election, TYT hosted townhalls with Sanders and [[Green Party of the United States|Green party]] candidate [[Jill Stein]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> In the late 2010s, other TYT townhalls were held with Sanders on the [[Climate change mitigation|climate change crisis]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=188.}}</ref> Several hosts for TYT have expressed support for Sanders.<ref name=\"Taylor204\">{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=J. Benjamin|title=Extreme Media and American Politics: In Defense of Extremity|year=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319411835|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4VqXDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Extreme+Media+and+American+Politics:+In+Defense+of+Extremity#v=snippet&q=Young%20Turks&f=false|pages=204|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Kolehmainen22\">{{cite journal|last=Kolehmainen|first=Pekka|title=Social media narratives as political fan fiction in the 2016 US presidential election|journal=European Journal of American Studies|volume=12|issue=12\u20132|year=2017|ref=harv|doi=10.4000/ejas.12147}} para. 22.</ref><ref name=\"Hellinger109\">{{cite book|last=Hellinger|first=Daniel C.|title=Conspiracies and Conspiracy Theories in the Age of Trump|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319981581|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U3hvDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Conspiracies+and+Conspiracy+Theories+in+the+Age+of+Trump#v=onepage&q=uygur&f=false|pages=109|ref=harv}}</ref> \n\n[[File:TYT Medicare For All sign (48434414206).jpg|thumb|250px|TYT sign supporting [[Medicare for All]]]]\nThe network supports political candidates who are from the same ideological persuasion.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Following the 2016 presidential election, Uygur co-founded Justice Democrats, an organisation that seeks to get progressive candidates elected into office.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\"/> During the US mid-term elections (2018), the network endorsed all candidates from the Justice Democrats (JD).<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\"/> TYT was the first network to give airtime to progressive candidates such as [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] to discuss policies and contrast themselves from electoral opponents on its shows like ''Rebel HQ'', a half an hour interview based program created in 2017.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\"/> In 2018, TYT also featured other progressive political candidates on ''Rebel HQ'' such as [[Richard Ojeda]] during his congressional run, gubernatorial candidates [[Cynthia Nixon]] who ran in [[New York (state)|New York State]] and [[Christine Hallquist]] in [[Vermont]] to discuss their policies.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\"/> \n\nAs a platform for online and offline civic engagement and political action, ''Rebel HQ'' offers information about a candidate, their website and campaign.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> The show informs viewers on how they can contact politicians, assist progressive candidates affiliated or unaffiliated with the Justice Democrats through donations or to participate by volunteering, canvassing and attending events like rallies in local communities.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191192\">{{cite book|last1=Grigoryan|first1=Nune|last2=Suetzl|first2=Wolfgang|chapter=Hybridized political participation|editor1-last=Atkinson|editor1-first=Joshua D.|editor2-last=Kenix|editor2-first=Linda|title=Alternative Media Meets Mainstream Politics: Activist Nation Rising|year=2019|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781498584357|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D_CYDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Alternative+Media+Meets+Mainstream+Politics:+Activist+Nation+Rising#v=snippet&q=TYT&f=false|pages=190, 191\u2013192|ref=harv}}</ref> TYT's online platforms facilitate the encouragement of civic participation with the political system that in 2018 assisted Justice Democrats in getting 7 congressional victories, 25 candidates during the general election and 78 in the primaries.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=191.}}</ref> After Ocasio-Cortez became a congresswomen, TYT has continued to cover and defend her from slants by the political and media elite.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=190}}</ref> Other Justice Democrats congressional members like [[Ro Khanna]] and [[Rashida Tlaib]] have appeared on TYT discussing progressive policies and issues.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|pp=190-191.}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, during a high-profile Democratic presidential candidate campaign weekend in Iowa, TYT and a group of supporters launched the Progressive Economic Pledge campaign, challenging presidential candidates to sign. The pledge is to support higher wages, Medicare for All, Green New Deal, college for all and the end of private campaign financing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/448565-young-turks-founder-voting-for-biden-over-trump-would-be-no-brainer|title=Young Turks founder: Voting for Biden over Trump would be 'no-brainer'|last=Bonn|first=Tess|date=2019-06-14|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713182146/https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/448565-young-turks-founder-voting-for-biden-over-trump-would-be-no-brainer|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://join.tyt.com/pledge/|title=Join TYT\"s Progressive Economic Pledge|website=join.tyt.com|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629084940/https://join.tyt.com/pledge/|archive-date=June 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-November 2019, Uygur filed to run for Congress in [[California's 25th congressional district|California's 25th district]], a seat recently vacated by the resignation of [[Katie Hill (politician)|Katie Hill]], an office also being pursued by former Trump campaign aide [[George Papadopoulos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/election-2020/cenk-uygur-files-to-run-for-congress-in-katie-hills-district/|title=Cenk Uygur Files to Run For Congress in Katie Hill's District|date=2019-11-13|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cenk-uygur-young-turks-files-run-congresswoman-katie-hills-seat-one-day-after-endorsing-1471638|title=Cenk Uygur of 'The Young Turks' files to run for Congresswoman Katie Hill's seat one day after endorsing Sanders|last=Malaea|first=Marika|date=2019-11-13|website=Newsweek|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/cenk-uygur-congress-run-katie-hill-california|title=Liberal host Cenk Uygur files for congressional run in Katie Hill's former district|last=Wulfsohn|first=Joseph|date=2019-11-13|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> Uygur as a result took a leave of absence while campaigning but continued to make appearances as co-host during designated breaks in his campaign schedule, with Kasparian acting as the executive producer and assuming editorial control of the program during this timeframe.\n\n== Name controversy ==\n\nAccording to Cenk Uygur, the name of the show was chosen because it is a popular colloquialism traditionally meaning a young radical who fights the status quo.<ref name=\"pastemagazine\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/01/why-cenk-uygur-is-getting-confronted-about-the-nam.html |title=Why Cenk Uygur Is Getting Confronted about the Name \"The Young Turks,\" and Why It Matters |first=Monica |last=Hunter-Hart |date=January 5, 2017 |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328230829/https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/01/why-cenk-uygur-is-getting-confronted-about-the-nam.html |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the American Heritage Dictionary, it stands for \"a young progressive or insurgent member of an institution, movement, or political party.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=young+turk&submit.x=0&submit.y=0 |title=Young Turk |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Publishing Company |website=The American Heritage Dictionary |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328215243/https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=young+turk&submit.x=0&submit.y=0 |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Safire |first=William |title=Safire's Political Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2008 |page=826 |isbn=978-0195343342}}</ref> The phrase has a history of being used in Western politics. It was used by [[Young Turks (U.S. politics)|a rebellious group of Congressmen]] within the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], of which [[Gerald Ford]] was a prominent member, who had become disenchanted with the course of the Party during the early 1960s as well as other [[Young Turks (disambiguation)|political groups around the world]]. However, the Young Turks show has been criticized for the name, as the original [[Young Turks]] political movement in the Ottoman Empire committed the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\"pastemagazine\"/> and that in 1991 Cenk Uygur wrote an article in ''[[The Daily Pennsylvanian]]'' in which he promoted Armenian Genocide denial.<ref>Uygur, Cenk (November 20, 1991). {{cite web |url=https://dparchives.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/pennsylvania?a=d&d=tdp19911122-01.2.24 |title=Historical Fact or Falsehood? The Daily Pennsylvanian Digital Archives |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406114936/https://dparchives.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/pennsylvania?a=d&d=tdp19911122-01.2.24 |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, he rescinded these statements, arguing: \"My mistake at the time was confusing myself for a scholar of history, which I most certainly am not. I don\u2019t want to make the same mistake again, so I am going to refrain from commenting on the topic of the Armenian Genocide, which I do not know nearly enough about.\"<ref>[https://legacy.tyt.com/2016/04/22/rescinding-daily-pennsylvanian-article/ Rescinding Daily Pennsylvanian Article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626085246/https://legacy.tyt.com/2016/04/22/rescinding-daily-pennsylvanian-article/ |date=June 26, 2019 }} Cenk Uygur, TYT Network; April 22, 2016</ref> Cenk Uygur has admitted to being mistaken about the Armenian Genocide and has recognized it as historical fact.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cenk Uygur recognizing Armenian Genocide |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Xib49Opls0 |publisher=Haypress News}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Young Turks}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.tyt.com/}}\n* {{YouTube|u=TheYoungTurks|The Young Turks}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Free Talk Live]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Podcast Awards|Podcast Award]] for<br/>Best Political Podcast/Best Political Website|years=2009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Free Talk Live]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TYT Network}}\n{{Current TV}}\n{{AAR}}\n{{Streamy Awards Winners CSS}}\n{{Portal bar|Internet|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young Turks, The}}\n[[Category:The Young Turks (talk show)| ]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Liberalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:California media]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:American talk radio programs]]\n[[Category:2002 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:Internet television channels]]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:American web series]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction web series]]\n[[Category:2005 web series debuts]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:Multi-channel networks]]\n[[Category:Streamy Award-winning channels, series or shows]]\n[[Category:2010s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Current TV original programming]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2005]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the political commentary web series|the Turkish reform movement|Young Turks|other meanings|Young Turks (disambiguation)|other meanings|TYT}}\n{{Short description|Online news show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Young Turks\n| image                    = TYT logo.svg\n| caption                  = Logotype\n| show_name_2              = TYT\n| genre                    = [[Political commentary]]<br/>[[News]]<ref name=\"PaoGhuHar2637\">{{cite journal|last1=Paolillo|first1=John|last2=Ghule|first2=Sharad|last3=Harper|first3=Brian|date=2019|title=A network view of social media platform history: Social structure, dynamics and content on Youtube|url=https://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/bitstream/10125/59701/0261.pdf|publisher=Proceedings of the 52nd Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences|accessdate=23 February 2020|pages=2637|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| creator                  = [[Cenk Uygur]]<br/>[[Ben Mankiewicz]]<ref name=\"Show\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks: Rebel Headquarters : News : Politics : Commentary |url=http://www.theyoungturks.com/show/index.htm |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515140446/http://www.theyoungturks.com/show/index.htm |archive-date=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br/>Dave Koller<ref name=\"Show\"/>\n| director                 = Jesus Godoy<ref name=\"Show\"/><br/>Jacorey Palmer<ref name=\"Show\"/>\n| presenter                = [[Cenk Uygur]] {{small|(2002\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Ben Mankiewicz]] {{small|(2002\u20132007; contributor thereafter)}}<br/>[[Jill Pike]] {{small|(2002\u20132007)}}<br/>[[Ana Kasparian]] {{small|(2008\u2013present)}}<br/>[[John Iadarola]] {{small|(2012\u2013present)}}\n| theme_music_composer     = <!--[[APM Music]]-->\n| opentheme                = <!--\"Beatdown\"-->\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| num_seasons              = 16\n| num_episodes             = \n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = [[Ana Kasparian]]<br/>\n| location                 = [[Wilshire Boulevard]], California<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=262177544 |title=Company Overview of The Young Turks LLC |website=Bloomberg.com |access-date=October 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181022232601/https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=262177544 |archive-date=October 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 120 minutes {{small|(main program)}}<br/>Varied {{small|([[post-game show]])}}\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| network                  = [[Sirius Satellite Radio]] {{small|(2002\u20132009, 2009\u20132010, 2017\u2013present)}}<ref>{{cite web |title=TYT Is Now on SiriusXM |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kadM73UmqxA |website=YouTube |access-date=28 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516012853/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kadM73UmqxA |archive-date=May 16, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[Air America (radio network)|Air America]] {{small|(2006\u20132008)}}<br/>[[YouTube]] {{small|(2005\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Roku]] {{small|(2013\u20132016)}}<br/>[[Hulu]] {{small|(2014\u2013present)}}<br/>[[Current TV]] {{small|(2011\u20132013)}}<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news |title='The Young Turks' host Cenk Uygur bets on Web after Current TV |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/15/entertainment/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tronc|Tribune Publishing]] |date=August 15, 2013 |access-date=September 6, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917134847/http://articles.latimes.com/2013/aug/15/entertainment/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813 |archive-date=September 17, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[Pluto TV]] {{small|(2014\u2013present)}}<ref>{{cite web |title=We're now on Pluto TV |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2014/04/01/now-pluto-tv/ |website=TYT Network |access-date=16 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807073227/https://tytnetwork.com/2014/04/01/now-pluto-tv/ |archive-date=August 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><br/>[[YouTube TV]] {{small|(2018\u2013present)}}\n| picture_format           = '''Television/online:'''<br/>[[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]; 2005\u20132011),<br/>[[1080i]] ([[high-definition television|HDTV]]; 2011\u2013present)\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2002|02|14}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = \n| website                  = https://www.tyt.com\n| production_website       = \n}}\n\n'''''The Young Turks''''' ('''TYT''') is a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mediabiasfactcheck.com/the-young-turks/|title=The Young Turks|website=Media Bias/Fact Check|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref> [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] news and opinion show on [[YouTube]] that additionally appears on selected TV channels in the United States. TYT serves as the flagship program of the TYT Network, a [[multi-channel network]] of associated web series focusing on news and current events. TYT covers politics, lifestyle, pop culture, science, sport and other social topics.<ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/><ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\"/> The program was created by [[Cenk Uygur]], [[Ben Mankiewicz]], and Dave Koller. Currently co-hosted by Uygur, [[Ana Kasparian]] and [[John Iadarola]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wme-signs-political-hosts-young-874456|title=WME Signs Political Hosts The Young Turks (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=May 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517070736/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wme-signs-political-hosts-young-874456|archive-date=May 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> it is also often accompanied by various other in-studio contributors. The program presents an anti-establishment stance and provides commentary on topics of varying news genres. ''The Young Turks'' began as a [[radio program]] that premiered on February 14, 2002, on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]]; it was later carried on [[Air America (radio network)|Air America]], before launching a web series component in 2005 on YouTube. In 2018, Regional News Network offered it initially on [[WMCN-TV|WMCN]], its New Jersey broadcast television station. \n\nIn addition to being carried on the TYT Network and YouTube, it is also currently available on [[Prime Video|Amazon Prime Direct]], [[iTunes]], [[Hulu]], [[Roku]], on [[Pluto TV]] through a 24-hour feed and on social media platforms [[Instagram]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/><ref name=\"Digital Marketing\"/> It has spawned two [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] [[television series]], one that aired on [[Current TV]]<ref name=\"The Young Turks on Fusuion\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks return to cable TV for election-focused show on Fusion |url=http://mashable.com/2016/05/09/young-turks-fusion-election-show/ |website=Mashable |access-date=17 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181208191036/https://mashable.com/2016/05/09/young-turks-fusion-election-show/ |archive-date=December 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> from 2011 to 2013 and a second that debuted on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]] in 2016 as a limited-run program developed to cover the [[2016 United States presidential election]]. ''The Young Turks'' also served as the subject of a documentary, entitled ''[[Mad as Hell]]'', which was released in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madashellfilm.com |title=Mad As Hell |website=Madashellfilm.com |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722225757/http://www.madashellfilm.com/ |archive-date=July 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The network also has a linear channel on [[YouTube TV]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Throughout its existence, TYT has relied on small grassroots financial contributions from its viewership to sustain itself as an independent news organisation.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> In 2017, TYT sought to expand its media network and hire more staff through various venture capital fundraising efforts that raised $20-million.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/> The growth of the network over the years has made TYT the longest-running and \"largest online news show in the world\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/the-young-turks-celebrates-10th-anniversary-today/|title=The Young Turks Celebrates 10th Anniversary Today|date=2012-02-14|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/><ref name=\"Solaimanxii\"/>\n\n==Format==\n''The Young Turks'' [[Streaming media|live streams]] for up to three hours, with its story selection and associated commentary broken up by format. Issues that the show focuses on include national political news, the [[Campaign finance in the United States|influence of money in the political process]], drug policy, [[social security]], the privatization of public services, [[climate change]], the influence of [[religion]], [[abortion]] and [[reproductive rights]], [[civil and political rights|civil rights]] and issues of injustice towards [[Person of color|people of color]] and [[sexual minority|sexual minorities]], sexual morality, and the influence of [[corporate media|corporations, neutrality and establishment political thought]] on traditional news media. The program maintains a liberal/progressive ideology in its political commentary.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur on the success of The Young Turks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/cenk-uygur-young-turks |first=Chavala |last=Madlena |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=Guardian Media, LLC |date=April 26, 2010 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928091053/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/26/cenk-uygur-young-turks |archive-date=September 28, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Saltonstall>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Glenn Beck's right-wing rants go way too far, critics charge |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/fox-news-glenn-beck-right-wing-rants-critics-charge-article-1.382031 |first=David |last=Saltonstall |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |location=New York |date=September 12, 2009 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811102010/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/fox-news-glenn-beck-right-wing-rants-critics-charge-article-1.382031 |archive-date=August 11, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Cenk Uygur Sets Out to Take Down Traditional Television |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/141/young-turks-indeed.html |first=Tina |last=Dupuy |magazine=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |date=December 1, 2009 |access-date=January 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091218055722/http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/141/young-turks-indeed.html |archive-date=December 18, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenwood96\"/> Co-creator and host Cenk Uygur describes himself as an \"[[Independent (voter)|independent]] progressive\" and asserts that the show is aimed at the \"98 percent 'not in power'\" and what he describes as the 60 percent of Americans who hold progressive views.<ref name=independent/>\n\nThe first hour, which is occasionally hosted solo by Uygur but frequently has Ana Kasparian among other co-hosts, focuses on [[Politics of the United States|American politics]], foreign policy and [[breaking news]] headlines.<ref>{{cite news |title=On the media: For Young Turk Cenk Uygur, TV is the next frontier |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-onthemedia-20100908,0,435910.column |first=James |last=Rainey |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=September 8, 2010 |access-date=September 9, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009193226/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-et-onthemedia-20100908,0,435910.column |archive-date=October 9, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second hour \u2013 which is co-hosted by Uygur and Ana Kasparian \u2013 provides social commentary on a wide range of topics, both domestic and foreign. The program also features a [[post-game show]], in which Uygur and Kasparian discuss their personal lives. Uygur has regular bits and on-air interaction with other staff members who create and run the show, including among others Jes\u00fas Godoy, Dave Koller, Jayar Jackson and Steve Oh.\n\nEach Friday, ''The Young Turks'' features a [[panel show|panel]] of guests from the worlds of politics, journalism, pop culture, sports and comedy \u2013 dubbed the \"TYT Power Panel\" \u2013 that is led by Uygur and John Iadarola in the first hour and Kasparian in the second hour. Along with Iadarola, other fill-in hosts and recurring guests include series co-creator/contributor [[Ben Mankiewicz]], comedian [[Jimmy Dore]], television personality [[Brian Unger]], [[Hasan Piker]], Becca Frucht, [[Brett Erlich]], Wes Clark Jr., [[Michael Shure]], [[Cara Santa Maria]], RJ Eskow, Gina Grad, Samantha Schacher, and Jayde Lovell.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Ana Kasparian and Cenk Uygur hosting The Young Turks (26942061744).jpg|thumb|250px|[[Cenk Uygur]] (left) and [[Ana Kasparian]] (right) on the show's set in 2015]]\n''The Young Turks'' is broadcast in a two-to-three hour live stream format, which airs Monday through Fridays at 3:00&nbsp;p.m. Pacific Time. The program was originally based out of the living room of creator/host Cenk Uygur, but it moved production to a small office in [[Los Angeles]] after the show hired a limited staff to produce the program. When the program was given a secondary live show on Current TV in 2011, the network provided a larger studio in Los Angeles to house its television and online broadcasts; production was forced to leave the facility after Current TV was sold to [[Al Jazeera]], prior to the network's conversion into the now-defunct generalized news service [[Al Jazeera America]].\n\nIn 2013, ''The Young Turks{{'}}'' production staff relocated temporarily to new studio quarters at YouTube Space LA in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Digital Marketing\">{{cite web |title=Life after cable: The Young Turks Network launches a Roku app |url=http://www.learn-digital-marketing.com/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |website=Digital Marketing |access-date=July 31, 2013 |quote=The channel's new owners have opted not to keep The Young Turks on the network due to it being political commentary rather than reporting/analysis. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925194401/http://www.learn-digital-marketing.com/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |archive-date=September 25, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2013, ''The Young Turks'' launched an [[Indiegogo]] campaign, aimed at raising $250,000 in order to build a new studio. Fundraising completed with $400,000 being raised.<ref name=\"Indiegog Campaign\">{{cite web |access-date=December 29, 2016 |url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/tyt-let-s-build-it-together-the-young-turks |title=TYT \u2013 Let's Build It Together! The Young Turks |website=Indiegogo |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507004824/https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/tyt-let-s-build-it-together-the-young-turks/ |archive-date=May 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The program moved its production facilities and staff operations to a new studio facilities in Los Angeles later that year, with construction of their new studio being completed in June 2015. In 2017, TYT sought to expand its media network and hire more staff through various venture capital fundraising efforts that raised $20-million.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Radio program===\n''The Young Turks'' was originally developed as a radio [[talk show]] that was similar in format to a Los Angeles-based [[public-access television|public access]] television program that Cenk Uygur had hosted, titled ''The Young Turk''. With the help of friend [[Ben Mankiewicz]] (with whom he had previously worked), his childhood friend Dave Koller, and [[Jill Pike]], Uygur began ''The Young Turks'' as a radio program in February 2002 on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]].<ref name=\"Greenwood96\">{{cite book|last=Greenwood|first=Sue|title=Future Journalism: Where we are and where we're going|year=2017|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317192664|url=https://books.google.com/?id=L4U0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT7#v=onepage&q=TYT%20network&f=false|pages=96|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/><ref name=Guardian/> On the show's website, the title is explained as deriving from the English-language phrase \"Young Turk\", meaning a \"progressive or insurgent member of an institution, movement, or political party\" or a \"young person who rebels against authority or societal expectations\".<ref>{{cite web |title=About. TYT network details |url=http://www.tytnetwork.com/info/ |website=TYT Network |access-date=June 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711124427/http://www.tytnetwork.com/info/ |archive-date=July 11, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the program received attention for its 99-hour \"Live on Air Filibuster,\" conducted during Congressional hearings for the [[Samuel Alito Supreme Court nomination|nomination]] of [[Samuel Alito]] to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Hosts including [[Thom Hartmann]] and [[Crooks and Liars|John Amato]] filled in during the event, to allow the show's regular hosts and contributors to rest or take breaks.<ref name=\"LAT 2006\">{{cite news |title=Can't get on the network? Get on the Net |url=https://articles.latimes.com/print/2006/mar/19/entertainment/ca-turks19 |first=Matea |last=Gold |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=March 19, 2006 |access-date=July 10, 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127162319/http://articles.latimes.com/print/2006/mar/19/entertainment/ca-turks19 |archive-date=January 27, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to signing a distribution deal to carry the program on [[Air America (radio network)|Air America]] in 2006, the show was broadcast on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]],<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> on Sirius Left 143 and later 146, airing weekdays from 6:00 to 9:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern Time; a day-behind rebroadcast of the program aired on Sirius Talk Central 148 weekday afternoons from 12:00 to 2:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern. Being carried exclusively on Sirius for several years, ''The Young Turks'' was the first show to air exclusively on Sirius Left that was not distributed through a syndication network.{{citation needed|date=September 2010}} TYT was also carried by KFH (1330 AM and 98.7 FM, now [[KNSS (AM)]] and [[KNSS-FM]]) in [[Wichita, Kansas]] each weeknight from 7:00 to 9:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]] and [[webcast]] by RadioPower.org.\n\nOn February 2, 2009, TYT was removed from the broadcast schedule of [[America Left]], a progressive talk channel carried on Sirius/XM Channel 167, and replaced by an additional hour of ''[[The Bill Press Show]]''. The program returned to Sirius/XM on March 16, 2009. In late 2010, TYT announced through its [[Facebook]] page that it would discontinue carrying the program on Sirius/XM Satellite Radio; the last edition of ''The Young Turks'' to be carried on the service aired on November 19, 2010. TYT rejoined Sirius/XM in 2017 with the show being run on [[SiriusXM Progress]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165634/the-young-turks-dean-obeidallah-join-siriusxm-prog |title='The Young Turks,' Dean Obeidallah Join SiriusXM Progress Lineup |website=AllAccess.com |date=May 11, 2017 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122005557/https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/165634/the-young-turks-dean-obeidallah-join-siriusxm-prog |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Web series===\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | align = right\n | width   = 120\n | image1  = Cenk Uygur by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n | alt1  = A man\n | caption1 = \n | image2  = Ana Kasparian (27847150002).jpg\n | caption2 = \n | alt2 = A woman\n | footer = [[Cenk Uygur]] (''top, 2016'') and [[Ana Kasparian]] (''bottom, 2016'') host the web series.\n}}\n''The Young Turks'' was the first daily streaming online talk show, having begun airing in that format in 2006,<ref name=Guardian/> with an official website on the internet and a channel hosted on Youtube.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The show provides in-depth coverage on politics regarding topics, events and other issues.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\"/> \n\nIn August 2007, Ben Mankiewicz left the show to serve as a contributor for [[TMZ (website)|TMZ]]'s syndicated entertainment news program ''[[TMZ on TV]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Young Turks: Ben Mankiewicz Has Left the Building |url=http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2007/8/20/11398/6352/Diary/Ben-Mankiewicz-Has-Left-the-Building |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717044118/http://www.theyoungturks.com/story/2007/8/20/11398/6352/Diary/Ben-Mankiewicz-Has-Left-the-Building |archive-date=July 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> At roughly the same time, Jill Pike left to pursue a job in [[Washington, D.C.]] [[Ana Kasparian]], then working as an intern for the program, was hired to do pop culture-focused segments. Mankiewicz eventually returned to ''The Young Turks'' as a regular correspondent.\n\nDuring the [[United States elections, 2008|2008 elections]], the show developed close ties to [[Brave New Films]]. The program aired commercials for the independent film production company and featured actors such as [[Robert Greenwald]] and Jonathan Kim as guests.\n\nThe success of TYT is due to a large extent of their shift from radio to the internet through the broadcast of programming content on online platforms.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Uygur and co-host Kasparian applied a populist left branding and programming strategy that made TYT a successful global online organisation, with larger numbers of YouTube subscribers and viewers than several other notable news networks like [[FOX]], [[MSNBC]] and [[CNN]].<ref name=\"Peck105108\">{{cite book|last=Peck|first=Reece|title=Fox populism: Branding conservatism as working class|year=2019|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781108496766|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JFR-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PR9&dq=Fox+Populism:+Branding+Conservatism+as+Working+Class#v=onepage&q=TYT%20uygur&f=false|pages=105, 108|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The presence of TYT on Youtube has given the network a platform to democratise production of content and practices associated with its online distribution through an ability to share, comment and like material on its channel.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> Through likes and shares of TYT content on many online platforms, audience members have become a \"virtual word of mouth\" expanding the network's reach to other people with similar views and stimulating the growth of the TYT community.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> \n\nSupport by viewers for alternative media outlets like TYT adopting new technology has meant the network was able to overcome being a small sized organisation of the traditional alternative media landscape.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The emergence of TYT in the digital era has resulted in fewer operational costs regarding organising and communication.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> TYT nonetheless has relied on small grassroots financial contributions from its viewers that gave it the ability to emerge as an alternative media organisation that does not advocate for the interests of corporations.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\"/> The financial contributions TYT received went to renting a studio, and to purchase production equipment and furniture.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185186\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|pp=185-186.}}</ref> By 2010, TYT employed people and maintained a budget resembling the size of a small newspaper.<ref name=\"May506\"/> \n\nOn July 30, 2013, ''The Young Turks'' launched a TYT Network [[mobile app|app]] on Roku,<ref>{{cite web |title=Life after cable: The Young Turks Network launches a Roku app |url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/07/30/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |website=VentureBeat |date=July 30, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804064136/http://venturebeat.com/2013/07/30/life-after-cable-the-young-turks-network-launches-a-roku-app/ |archive-date=August 4, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> which features much of the same content that is already available for free through the program's YouTube channel,<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl185\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=185.}}</ref> which has over 4.2&nbsp;million subscribers and generates 50 million monthly views. The network is among the few online channels to generate more than 1&nbsp;billion views since launching on YouTube, which does not market a channel on the Roku app store. Young Turks COO Steve Oh acknowledged that making the TYT Network available on Roku was the first part of a strategy to continue the network's growth, regardless of what medium in which its viewers are watching its content, with the intent to figure out a way to monetize its programming through multiple distribution channels, rather than relying on one or two larger channels (such as YouTube or cable television distribution). The network also announced plans to unveil native apps for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices. Oh also noted that the network's representatives were speaking with other media platforms about expanding its programming.\n\nIn April 2014, ''The Young Turks'' began offering its content on [[Hulu]]. With this, it began providing a condensed 30-minute version of the program featuring excerpts from the full two-hour daily show, along with a 30-minute weekly version of its daily pop-culture show ''PopTrigger'', with other shows being added shortly afterward. Oh stated on the Hulu launch that, \"as TYT Network has grown from a single show to an entire network, we've consistently found ways to bring our shows to more people[..] We've long admired Hulu as a leader of online video and both parties saw an opportunity to bring digitally-native politics and pop culture talk shows to Hulu's audience.\" He also stated that the company is pitching shows to cable network, but had no immediate plans to revive a television broadcast as either a relaunched program or a show similar in format to the one it formerly produced for Current TV.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur's Young Turks Network launches shows on Hulu |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-the-young-turks-network-launches-shows-on-hulu-20140321-story.html |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=March 24, 2014 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315035048/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-the-young-turks-network-launches-shows-on-hulu-20140321-story.html |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe website's yearly revenue was roughly US$3&nbsp;million in 2013. According to Cenk Uygur, \"about a third of the revenue comes from subscriptions, and the rest comes from YouTube ads.\" At that time, the company maintained a staff of 30 employees.<ref name=faughnder /> In 2014, the company received a US$4&nbsp;million investment from Roemer, Robinson, Melville & Co., LLC, a [[private equity firm]] led by Republican former Louisiana Governor [[Buddy Roemer]].<ref>{{cite news |title=YouTube Network The Young Turks Raises $4 Million To Expand To New Platforms |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/04/16/the-young-turks-4m/ |last1=Lawler |first1=Ryan |website=[[TechCrunch]] |date=16 April 2014 |access-date=January 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408000647/http://techcrunch.com/2014/04/16/the-young-turks-4m/ |archive-date=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2016, TYT Network launched a crowdfunding campaign aiming to raise [[United States dollar|US$]]2&nbsp;million for the hiring of four further investigative teams.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Young Turks Raising $2 Million To Fund Four Investigative Teams |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/12/09/the-young-turks-fundraising-investigative-journalism |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=December 9, 2016 |access-date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107112700/http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/12/09/the-young-turks-fundraising-investigative-journalism/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Five months later, the aim was met.<ref>{{cite web |title=TYT Reaches $2 Million in Fundraising Campaign |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2017/05/18/tyt-reaches-2-million-in-fundraising-campaign |website=The Young Turks |access-date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107222226/https://tytnetwork.com/2017/05/18/tyt-reaches-2-million-in-fundraising-campaign/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2017, it was announced that The Young Turks have raised $20&nbsp;million in venture-capital from 3L Capital, WndrCo (owned by businessman [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]]),<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/young-turks-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco-funding-1202518938/|title=Jeffrey Katzenberg's WndrCo Invests in TYT Network as Part of $20 Million Round|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=August 8, 2017|access-date=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423153740/https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/young-turks-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco-funding-1202518938/|archive-date=April 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |title=The Young Turks Raises $20 Million From Jeffrey Katzenberg's WndrCo, Greycroft, 3L Capital, More |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/08/08/the-young-turks-20-million-funding-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco/ |website=TubeFilter |date=August 8, 2017 |access-date=Oct 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107024123/http://www.tubefilter.com/2017/08/08/the-young-turks-20-million-funding-jeffrey-katzenberg-wndrco/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |last1=Tani |first1=Maxwell |title=Progressive media outlet The Young Turks has raised $20&nbsp;million in venture-capital funding and plans to double its staff |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/young-turks-fundraising-venture-capital-criticism-2017-8 |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=31 October 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813142351/https://www.businessinsider.com/young-turks-fundraising-venture-capital-criticism-2017-8 |archive-date=August 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Greycroft]], and [[e.ventures]]. TYT stated it would use the funds to \"hire additional management execs and creative talent, as well as enhance its subscription-video offering and expand marketing initiatives\". Shawn Colo, managing partner of 3L Capital, joined the TYT Network's board.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nTYT operates under a strategy of diversifying its finances that involves the airing of socially responsible advertisements, offering subscriptions for TYT membership, selling its own merchandise and other investments.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>  Among its advertising partners is Aspiration Bank, an organisation involved in \"socially conscious and sustainable banking services\" and whom TYT presents as different from other banks and their fossil fuel and campaign financing investments.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Due to popular demand from viewers, TYT established an online outlet selling its own label branded merchandise, such as t-shirts, that are often designed and voted upon through the input of its audience.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Its online subscription membership has two plans, \"insider\" offering full web content access and discounts, and \"activist\", offering additional access to its townhalls and political events.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> \n\nFollowing the 2016 election, TYT fundraised for small grassroots donations among its members, raising thousands of dollars and created a media division named ''TYT Investigates'' devoted to investigative journalism with the aim to hold people with power to account.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> Operating as a watchdog outfit, ''TYT Investigates'' through its investigative journalistic team reports on issues such as inequalities in the economic system, power held by corporations, and other topics sidelined by traditional media like the views of ordinary citizens at political events.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> For example, TYT journalist Emma Vigland has attended US President [[Donald Trump]]'s political rallies and interviewed supporters.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> \n\nIn November 2017, TYT fired field reporter [[Jordan Chariton]] over [[Weinstein effect|sexual assault allegations]] made against him by the Huffington Post.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/11/20/young-turks-and-reporter-abruptly-part-ways-following-sexual-assault-allegations/ |title=The Young Turks and Reporter Abruptly Part Ways Following Sexual Assault Allegations |last=Ch\u00e1vez |first=A\u00edda |date=21 November 2017 |website=[[The Intercept]] |language=en-US |access-date=22 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171121011705/https://theintercept.com/2017/11/20/young-turks-and-reporter-abruptly-part-ways-following-sexual-assault-allegations/ |archive-date=November 21, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Lima\"/> Chariton denied the accusations, considered legal actions<ref name=\"Lima\">{{cite news|last=Lima|first=Cristiano|title=Ousted 'Young Turks' reporter files $23.5 million suit against HuffPost|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/13/young-turks-huffington-post-295474|agency=Politico|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=28 February 2020||url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and later he settled the matter with TYT.<ref name=\"Flood\">{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Brian|title=Liberal HuffPost scraps contributor network amid 'tsunami of false information'|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/liberal-huffpost-scraps-contributor-network-amid-tsunami-of-false-information|agency=FOX News|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=28 February 2020|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-December 2017, Politico reported that TYT was courting former [[CBS Evening News]] anchor [[Dan Rather]] to host a news show.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calderone |first1=Michael |url=https://www.politico.com/media/newsletters/morning-media/2017/12/13/alabama-shocker-the-post-and-the-times-how-hannity-undermines-mueller-acostas-access-threatened-001400 |title=Alabama shocker \u2014 'The Post' and The Times \u2014 Hannity undermines Mueller \u2014 'Forged' Schumer doc shopped \u2014 Acosta's access threatened |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=22 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012121907/https://www.politico.com/media/newsletters/morning-media/2017/12/13/alabama-shocker-the-post-and-the-times-how-hannity-undermines-mueller-acostas-access-threatened-001400 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On January 21, 2018, TYT confirmed that it will show ''The News with Dan Rather'', a half-hour \"untraditional evening newscast\" weekly on Mondays in the time slot before the main Young Turks show.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/01/21/media/dan-rather-the-young-turks/index.html |title=Dan Rather launching weekly show with progressive outlet The Young Turks Network |last=Darcy |first=Oliver |work=CNN Money |access-date=22 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205220923/https://money.cnn.com/2018/01/21/media/dan-rather-the-young-turks/index.html |archive-date=December 5, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2020, the [[International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees]] (IATSE) sought to unionise the production and post-production staff at TYT.<ref>[https://deadline.com/2020/02/iatse-launches-drive-to-unionize-the-young-turks-news-site-1202858884/ IATSE Launches Drive To Unionize The Young Turks News Site] By David Robb, Labor Editor, www.deadline.com, February 12, 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.iatse.net/news/employees-young-turks-announce-unionization EMPLOYEES AT THE YOUNG TURKS ANNOUNCE UNIONIZATION] www.iatse.net, Tuesday, February, 18, 2020.</ref> Uygur urged his employees not to, as he stated TYT is a small media organisation and the move would endanger its financial viability, however the network has supported its workers holding a secret ballot to unionise.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\"/><ref name=\"Floodun\"/> Employees have expressed support for an open ballot and the bargaining process is ongoing.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\"/><ref name=\"Floodun\">{{cite news|last=Flood|first=Brian|title=Young Turks founder Cenk Uygur says a union would hurt progressive outlet|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/young-turks-union-cenk-uygur|agency=FOX News|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Linear channel===\nOn May 17, 2018, The Young Turks launched a 24-hour linear channel on [[YouTube TV]] which includes all of TYT's current shows and four new shows called ''The Damage Report'', ''\"#NoFilter\"'',''\"The Happy Half Hour\"'' and ''\"Old-School Sports\"''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/youtube-tv-tastemade-young-turks-linear-channels-1202812759/ |title=YouTube TV Launches Tastemade, TYT Network 24-Hour Linear Channels |last=Spangler |first=Todd |date=2018-05-17 |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=2018-05-18 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828212710/https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/youtube-tv-tastemade-young-turks-linear-channels-1202812759/ |archive-date=August 28, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The channel has since been made available on The Roku Channel, Pluto TV, and Xumo as well.\n\n==Reception==\n* In September 2018, the company launched a membership drive, reporting the number of members to be around 27,000.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peterson |first1=Tim |title=The Young Turks now has 27k paying subscribers accounting for half of its revenue |url=https://digiday.com/media/young-turks-now-27k-paying-subscribers-accounting-half-revenue/ |access-date=10 September 2018 |website=[[DigiDay]] |date=29 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921122009/https://digiday.com/media/young-turks-now-27k-paying-subscribers-accounting-half-revenue/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* As of August 2018, TYT had approximately 27,000 paying subscribers online.<ref name=faughnder/>\n* As of September 2017, the program's [[YouTube]] channel averages a daily hit count of 2 million views per day.<ref>{{cite web |title=YouTube Top 100 Most Viewed News &amp; Politics Video Producers |url=http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-viewed-news-politics |website=Vidstatsx.com |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407202320/http://vidstatsx.com/youtube-top-100-most-viewed-news-politics |archive-date=April 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* By August 2016, Cenk Uygur reported that number of paid subscribers had increased to more than 23,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2016/08/22/how-can-you-create-the-most-progressive-show-on-the-planet/ |title=How You Can Create The Most Progressive Show on the Planet |website=The Young Turks |via=YouTube |access-date=April 3, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823173153/https://tytnetwork.com/2016/08/22/how-can-you-create-the-most-progressive-show-on-the-planet/ |archive-date=August 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* By October 2016, the total number of views for the TYT Network's YouTube channel had surpassed 3&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"3billion\">{{cite av media |title=TYT Network About Section |url=https://www.youtube.com/user/TheYoungTurks/about |publisher=TYT Network |via=YouTube |date=November 17, 2017 |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171230173811/https://www.youtube.com/user/TheYoungTurks/about |archive-date=December 30, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* On April 20, 2013, ''The Young Turks'' announced that its YouTube channel had received over 1&nbsp;billion video views.<ref name=\"The Young Turks Hits 1 Billion Views!\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks Hits 1 Billion Views! |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tJ7ei0a1ZZE |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |access-date=April 21, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016203359/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tJ7ei0a1ZZE |archive-date=October 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2006 article, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' contributing writer Paul Bedard described TYT as \"the loudly liberal counter to the right-leaning presets on my Sirius Satellite Radio.\"<ref name=USNews>{{cite magazine |title=Air America's young turks |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/paulyblog/2006/09/air_americas_young_turks.htm |first=Paul |last=Bedard |magazine=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=September 13, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113202025/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/politics/whispers/paulyblog/2006/09/air_americas_young_turks.htm |archivedate=January 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[The Independent]]'' described it as \"the most-watched online news show in the world.\"<ref name=independent>{{cite news |title=Cenk Uygur's The Young Turks: This YouTube news bulletin is challenging the fogeys of US TV |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/opinion/cenk-uygurs-the-young-turks-this-youtube-news-bulletin-is-challenging-the-fogeys-of-us-tv-9761069.html |first=Ian |last=Burrell |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=September 28, 2014 |access-date=January 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108211629/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/opinion/cenk-uygurs-the-young-turks-this-youtube-news-bulletin-is-challenging-the-fogeys-of-us-tv-9761069.html |archive-date=January 8, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe network is reliant on its multimedia platforms to attract online viewers and its audience are either \"young, educated, affluent and politically interested\" people who consume news from online sources.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> As a result of ongoing TYT membership drives, its base of subscribed members has grown numbering 32,000 in 2019.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> Over 12 million viewers (2019) are subscribed to its multiple online channels.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> TYT has become one of the largest watched online networks with its videos seen over 8 billion times (2019).<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/> TYT's [[Millennials|millennial]] viewership ranks the network first for news and politics across its online platforms.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>  \n\n===Awards and nominations===\n''The Young Turks'' has won and been nominated for numerous Internet content awards, including, but not limited to: \n\n* In 2009, the program won in the Political category at the [[Podcast Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |title=2009 Podcast Awards Winners |url=http://www.podcastconnect.com/2009/12/2009-podcast-awards-winners/ |first=Todd |last=Cochrane |website=[[Podcast Awards]] |date=December 12, 2009 |access-date=December 14, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216071508/http://www.podcastconnect.com/2009/12/2009-podcast-awards-winners/ |archive-date=December 16, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won for \"Best Political News Site\" at the [[Mashable#Mashable Awards|Mashable Open Web Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Open Web Awards 2009: The Winners |url=http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/ |first=Pete |last=Cashmore |website=[[Mashable]] |date=December 16, 2009 |access-date=January 17, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301163609/http://mashable.com/2009/12/16/open-web-awards-2009-50-winners/ |archive-date=March 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In [[2nd Streamy Awards|2010]], it was nominated for a [[Streamy Awards|Streamy Award]] for \"Best News or Political Web Series\" and the \"Audience Choice Award for Best Web Series\".<ref>{{cite web |title=2nd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/2010-nominees/ |website=[[Streamy Awards]] |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508013524/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/2010-nominees/ |archive-date=May 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2011, the program won in the News category at the [[Shorty Awards#Third Annual Shorty Awards|Third Annual]] [[Shorty Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |title=3rd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://3rd.shortyawards.com/ |website=[[Shorty Awards]] |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504223654/http://3rd.shortyawards.com/ |archive-date=May 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and won for \"Best News and Political Series\" at [[2011 Webby Awards|that year's]] [[Webby Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=15th Annual Webby Awards Nominees & Winners |url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?media_id=97&season=15#film_news_series |website=[[Webby Award]]s |access-date=June 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5xvYAKEsL?url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?media_id=97&season=15#film_news_series |archive-date=April 14, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2012, it won in the Best Video Podcast category at the [[Podcast Awards]] .<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |title=Podcast Award Winners 2005-2014 |access-date=May 15, 2016 |website=[[Podcast Awards]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Lh9tnIpR?url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |archive-date=December 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In [[3rd Streamy Awards|2013]], the program was nominated for two Streamy Awards in the Best News and Culture Series and Audience Choice Award for Series of the Year categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=3rd Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/3rd-annual-nominees/ |website=Streamy Awards |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301233651/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/3rd-annual-nominees/ |archive-date=March 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2015, ''The Young Turks'' also won a Streamy Award in the News and Culture category.<ref>{{cite web |title=5th Annual Winners & Nominees |url=http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/5th-annual-nominees-winners/ |website=Streamy Awards |access-date=May 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816150658/http://www.streamys.org/nominees-winners/5th-annual-nominees-winners/ |archive-date=August 16, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2017, TYT won the Shorty Awards Audience Honor for the Best in Overall YouTube Presence.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>\n\nOther awards won by ''The Young Turks'' in the 2010s were \"Best Political News Site\" and the  \"People's Voice Webby Award\" in all 5 of its categories.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\"/>\n\n==Television spin-offs==\n\n===''The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur''===\nThe first linear television incarnation of the program began as an hour-long show that premiered on [[Current TV]] on December 5, 2011. Co-created and hosted by Cenk Uygur (who executive produced the series with original program co-creator Dave Koller, with Jesus Godoy, Jayar Jackson and Mark Register serving as producers), the program was co-presented by Ana Kasparian, with Ben Mankiewicz, Michael Shure, Brian Unger, Wes Clark Jr. and RJ Eskow as contributors and correspondents. It was filmed at studio facilities in the [[Los Angeles]] suburb of [[Culver City, California|Culver City]].\n\nCurrent TV announced the launch of a separate television broadcast of ''The Young Turks'' on September 20, 2011, with the program intending to air Monday through Friday evenings at 7:00&nbsp;pm. Eastern Time beginning in the fourth quarter of 2011. It was the second news and opinion program to air on Current, alongside ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'', and was part of a strategy to refocus the network's prime time schedule around progressive talk programming (which was followed by the debut of ''[[The War Room with Jennifer Granholm]]'' in January 2012). According to the show's website, the show was titled ''The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur'' to differentiate itself from the popular web series.<ref name=\"CurrTV\">{{cite web |title=The Young Turks with Cenk Uygur |url=http://current.com/shows/the-young-turks/ |website=Current TV |access-date=August 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807205849/http://current.com/shows/the-young-turks/ |archive-date=August 7, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> For two years, the two separate shows were produced each Monday through Thursday, with a one-hour break between the production airtimes of the television and web shows. In a press release, representatives for Current described TYT as \"a group of progressive, outspoken journalists and commentators discussing politics and pop culture\" and founder Cenk Uygur as bringing a, \"uniquely progressive and topical commentary about politics and pop culture.\"<ref name=\"CurrTV\"/>\n\nOn January 2, 2013, Current TV was sold to Qatar-owned broadcaster [[Al Jazeera Media Network]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Al Jazeera targets US expansion after buying Current TV |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20896484 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=January 3, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820225517/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-20896484 |archive-date=August 20, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> which announced plans to reorganize the channel as [[Al Jazeera America]], focusing on world news and investigative content with a more neutral tone; with the move, the channel would discontinue its talk programming slate, including ''The Young Turks with Cenk Ugyur'', which ended its run on Current TV on August 15, 2013, shortly before the network's relaunch.<ref name=faughnder/><ref>{{cite web |title=TYT is Independent, Not Owned by Current or Al Jazeera |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yfJcyDmZHu0 |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |date=January 3, 2013 |access-date=August 5, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118210329/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yfJcyDmZHu0 |archive-date=January 18, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]],'' Uygur commented that with the discontinuance of the television broadcast, he was relieved to move on and focus on his web show and the TYT Network site, stating that he had been \"exhausted from doing the two shows at once\" and that he was glad to put his energies there, as he believes that the future of media will gravitate towards online content. Uygur also noted that he talked with Al Jazeera after the company bought Current, reaching a mutual agreement not to continue with the television broadcast due to the change in ideological tone that Al Jazeera America would maintain.<ref name=faughnder>{{cite news |title='The Young Turks' host Cenk Uygur bets on Web after Current TV |url=https://latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813,0,7754856.story |first=Ryan |last=Faughnder |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Publishing |date=August 12, 2013 |access-date=August 17, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816040307/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-young-turks-cenk-uygur-20130813,0,7754856.story |archive-date=August 16, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, members of ''The Young Turks{{'}}'' on-air contributing staff, such as [[Michael Shure]] (who served as a political and general assignment contributor), [[Cara Santa Maria]] (part of [[TechKnow]]) and [[Ben Mankiewicz]] (who worked as a movie critic), regularly appeared on Al Jazeera America. ''The Young Turks'' also maintain a partnership with Al Jazeera's digital channel [[AJ+]], in an arrangement first announced in March 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Exciting New Partnership! Check Out AJ+ |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XYC1IpG-8bg |author=The Young Turks |website=YouTube |date=March 20, 2015 |accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===''The Young Turks on Fusion''===\n''The Young Turks'' returned to television with a weekly, hour-long program on [[Fusion (TV channel)|Fusion]], ''The Young Turks on Fusion'', which premiered on September 12, 2016 for a twelve-week limited run. Hosted by Ana Kasparian and John Iadarola, the program \u2013 which was broadcast from college campuses around the United States, in a live-audience format modelled after [[ESPN]]'s ''[[College GameDay (football)|College GameDay]]'' \u2013 focused on coverage of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 United States presidential campaign]]. The show also featured Cenk Uygur, Jimmy Dore, Ben Mankiewicz, Hannah Cranston, [[Hasan Piker]], and Kim Horcher as contributors, as well as Fusion reporters and celebrity guest hosts.<ref>{{cite magazine |title='Young Turks' Will Get 12-Week Run on Fusion |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/young-turks-fusion-1201769078/ |first=Brian |last=Steinberg |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 9, 2016 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512005342/http://variety.com/2016/tv/news/young-turks-fusion-1201769078/ |archive-date=May 12, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fusion to Model Young Turks Show on ESPN's 'College Game Day' |url=https://thewrap.com/young-turks-fusion-espn-college-game-day/ |author=Brian Flood |website=[[The Wrap]] |publisher=The Wrap Media, LLC |date=May 9, 2016 |access-date=May 24, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514060750/http://www.thewrap.com/young-turks-fusion-espn-college-game-day/ |archive-date=May 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==TYT Network==\n''The Young Turks'' has spawned a [[multi-channel network]] of associated web series and shows, known as the TYT Network.\n\nSome of the programs produced for the service are produced in-house, among which include:\n* ''Aggressive Progressives'' \u2013 a weekly political talk and satire show that debuted in August 2016; it is co-hosted by Ron Placone, [[Graham Elwood]], and Steve Oh. It was co-hosted by [[Jimmy Dore]] from August 2016 until Dore's departure from the TYT Network in April 2019. It is streamed each Thursday to TYT Network members, with select segments being made available to all viewers each Saturday on ''The Young Turks''{{'}}s official YouTube channel.\n* ''TYT Sports'' \u2013 a sports commentary program that debuted in 2011; originally hosted by Cenk Uygur, Jayar Jackson and Ben Mankiewicz, Rick Strom took over as co-host in 2013 and was replaced in 2014 by Jason Rubin and Francis Maxwell.\n* \u2018\u2019Old School\u2019\u2019 - a more laid-back show hosted by Cenk Uygur and Ben Mankiewicz discussing every-day topics and telling stories \n* ''Styleogue'' \u2013 a fashion and lifestyle program that debuted in 2014, which is dedicated to affordable fashion.\n* ''Rebel HQ'' \u2013 an \"on-the-road\" political commentary and interview program formerly<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/jordan-chariton-young-turks-lawsuit-firing-259363 |title='Young Turks' reporter vows to sue over his firing |first=Cristiano |last=Lima |date=22 November 2017 |website=Politico |access-date=27 November 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171123010218/https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/jordan-chariton-young-turks-lawsuit-firing-259363 |archive-date=November 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> hosted by reporter [[Jordan Chariton]], which was created to cover the 2016 United States presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Reporter Jumps to The Young Turks |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/jordan-chariton-wrap-young-turks/362758 |first=Richard |last=Horgan |website=[[Adweek]] |date=December 20, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420030001/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/jordan-chariton-wrap-young-turks/362758 |archive-date=April 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Young Turks Pushes More Political Coverage, Adds Jordan Chariton To Team |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/12/21/the-young-turks-jordan-chariton-2016-election/ |first=Bree |last=Brouwer |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=December 21, 2015 |access-date=April 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331204552/http://www.tubefilter.com/2015/12/21/the-young-turks-jordan-chariton-2016-election/ |archive-date=March 31, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The channel is now primarily hosted by Emma Vigeland and with other segments and interviews hosted by Cenk Uygur and Mark Thompson. Formerly ''TYT Politics''\n* ''TYT Interviews'' \u2013 an interview series conducted by Cenk Uygur, and occasionally by other hosts.\n* ''TYT Investigates'' \u2013 the investigative reporting division of The Young Turks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tytnetwork.com/investigates/|title=TYT Investigates|website=TYT Network.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903154757/https://tytnetwork.com/investigates/|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> hosted by Michael Tracey, [[Ryan Grim]], David Sirota, Eric Byler, Dylan Ratigan, Ken Klippenstein, and other reporters.\n* ''The Damage Report'' \u2013 morning show hosted by John Iadarola focused the most critical issues facing the U.S. today\n* ''#NoFilter'' \u2013 analysis and commentary from TYT host Ana Kasparian\n* ''The Happy Half Hour'' \u2013 hosted by Brett Erlich, it's a more upbeat and lighter look at the \"not bad\" news of the week\n* ''Old-School Sports'' \u2013 TYT Sports host Rick Strom & BlackSportsOnline Owner Robert Littal revisits and analyzes classic games and rivalries.\n* ''Murder with Friends'' - Grace Baldridge invites guests to talk about some of history's most notorious murderers.\n\nOther shows are not produced in-house:\n* ''[[The Majority Report]]'' \u2013 a news and politics show hosted by [[Sam Seder]], which is a video broadcast of Seder's daily online radio program.\n* ''[[Richard A. Fowler#The Richard Fowler Show|The Richard Fowler Show]]'' \u2013 a weekly political talk show hosted by [[Richard A. Fowler]].\n* ''Secular Talk'' \u2013 a daily political talk show hosted by Kyle Kulinski, which is also broadcast on the Secular Talk Radio and [[BlogTalkRadio]] online networks.\n* ''The Humanist Report'' \u2013 a progressive political YouTube channel and podcast hosted by political scientist Mike Figueredo that began in 2015.\n* ''[[The Bill Press Show]]'' \u2013 a daily talk show hosted by [[Bill Press]], which is broadcast online, over radio and on [[Free Speech TV]] that became affiliated with the TYT Network in November 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2016/11/22/bill-press-show-joins-as-tyt-network-partner/ |title=Bill Press Show Joins as TYT Network Partner |date=November 22, 2016 |website=TYT Network |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020611/https://tytnetwork.com/2016/11/22/bill-press-show-joins-as-tyt-network-partner/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Acronym TV \u2013 a commentary program focusing on policy and national security issues, hosted by Dennis Trainor Jr.\n* ''Absurdity Today'' \u2013 a news satire program, hosted by Juliana Forlano.\n* ''The Undercurrent'' \u2013 a talk program hosted by Lauren Windsor, which covers a broad variety of in-depth topics, and includes interviews with politicians, media figures and opinion makers, as well as documentaries.\n* ''The Lip TV'' \u2013 a commentary program which maintains a live and unscripted format with a panel of experts on varying subjects of focus.\n* ''Truth Mashup'' \u2013 a weekly [[Canada|Canadian]] comedy show, co-hosted by Bree Essrig (who formerly co-hosted ''Pop Trigger'') and comedian and media activist Ron Placone.\n* ''ScIQ'' \u2013 a bi-weekly infotainment series hosted by Jayde Lovell, an Australian-born [[neurophysiologist]] and director of science PR consulting firm ReAgency, which explores scientific topics.\n* ''Around the Nation with Jeff Waldorf'' aka ''TYT Nation'' \u2013 a talk show hosted by Jeff Waldorf.\n\nPrograms produced for the TYT Network that are no longer in production include:\n* ''thetopvlog'' \u2013 a series of [[vlog]]s by [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] political commentators that TYT helped launch in June 2010.\n* ''twenTYTwelve'' \u2013 a political interview and commentary program, hosted by [[Michael Shure]], that was launched in October 2011 to cover the [[United States elections, 2012|2012 United States elections]].\n* ''TYT Now'' \u2013 a commentary program that was hosted by columnist [[Tina Dupuy]] and Tim Mihalsky, which ran from May to August 2011.\n* ''WMB'' \u2013 a commentary program hosted by Ben Mankiewicz, Michael Shure and Wes Clark Jr., which ran from May to June 2011.\n* ''Reality Bites Back'' \u2013 a [[reality television]]-focused review series, hosted by Jacki Bray and Misty Kingma, which ran from May to July 2011.\n* ''ThinkTank'' \u2013 a science and social commentary program that originated in 2011 as ''TYT University'', before relaunching under its current format in 2014; hosted by Hannah Cranston alongside a rotation of guest co-hosts (including original co-host John Iadarola, who diminished his role on ''ThinkTank'' during 2017), the program deals with new facts, discoveries and perspectives on the world and people.<ref>{{cite web |title=YouTube Millionaires: For ThinkTank's John Iadarola, A Re-Brand Led To Success |url=http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/03/17/youtube-millionaires-think-tank-john-iadarola/ |first=Sam |last=Gutelle |website=[[Tubefilter]] |date=March 17, 2016 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703132844/http://www.tubefilter.com/2016/03/17/youtube-millionaires-think-tank-john-iadarola/ |archive-date=July 3, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The Point'' \u2013 a [[Current affairs (news format)|current affairs]] [[panel show]], hosted by Ana Kasparian, that debuted in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |title=30 Under 30 2016: Media |url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/media/ |first1=Emily |last1=Inverso |first2=Glynnis |last2=MacNicol |website=[[Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes, LLC |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612080916/http://www.forbes.com/30-under-30-2016/media/ |archive-date=June 12, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=Ana Kasparian From 'The Young Turks' Says Her Feminism Means Wearing Heels Whenever The Hell She Wants |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/124162-ana-kasparian-from-the-young-turks-says-her-feminism-means-wearing-heels-whenever-the-hell-she |first=Josephine |last=Yurcaba |magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=November 17, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618032203/http://www.bustle.com/articles/124162-ana-kasparian-from-the-young-turks-says-her-feminism-means-wearing-heels-whenever-the-hell-she |archive-date=June 18, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> but has been on hiatus since January, 2016.\n* ''Pop Trigger'' \u2013 an [[infotainment]] show, hosted by [[Brett Erlich]] and Grace Baldridge with a rotating slate of guest co-hosts, that provides intelligent conversation on pop culture news. Ran until August. 2018.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)-->\n* ''Nerd Alert'' \u2013 a show that focuses on news about technology, gaming, movies and online geek culture; hosted by Kim Horcher, the program [[Spin-off (media)|spun off]] from a segment that originated on ''TYT University''. Ran until August, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Young Turks' Kim Horcher joins #TalkingTechLive panel |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/08/15/young-turks-kim-horcher-joins-talkingtechlive-panel/31797695/ |first=Jefferson |last=Graham |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=August 15, 2015 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150256/http://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/08/15/young-turks-kim-horcher-joins-talkingtechlive-panel/31797695/ |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The News with Dan Rather'' \u2013 A weekly 30-minute rundown of current events with commentary hosted by ex-CBS News lead anchor [[Dan Rather]]. Filmed in Dan Rather's personal office in New York.<ref>{{cite web |title=Premieres Monday: The News with Dan Rather |url=https://tytnetwork.com/2018/01/21/premieres-monday-the-news-with-dan-rather |author=julietyt |website=[[TYT Network]] |date=January 21, 2018 |access-date=January 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124073047/https://tytnetwork.com/2018/01/21/premieres-monday-the-news-with-dan-rather/ |archive-date=January 24, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''What the Flick?!'' \u2013 a [[film criticism|film review]] series that began in 2010; it is hosted by Ben Mankiewicz, [[Christy Lemire]], Matt Atchity and [[Alonso Duralde]].<ref name=Guardian/> Guest critics have included Robert Abele, William Bibbiani, Grae Drake, Tim Grierson, Amy Nicholson, Witney Seibold, Dave White, and April Wolfe. Ran until August, 2018.\n\nPrograms no longer produced or owned by the TYT Network, but are still in production:\n* ''[[The Rubin Report]]'' (broke away in August 2015) \u2013 a comedy and current events [[panel show]], hosted by [[Dave Rubin]], that premiered in 2013; the program moved to [[RYOT News]] in 2015, and later to [[Ora TV]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report-young-turks-_n_2786849.html |title=Dave Rubin, Gay Radio Host And Comedian, Launches 'The Rubin Report' Panel Show |date=February 2, 2016 |website=[[HuffPost]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |first=Curtis |last=Wong |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810085026/http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report-young-turks-_n_2786849.html |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report_us_55b93fb5e4b095423d0dbad5 |title=Comedian And LGBT Advocate Dave Rubin Brings 'The Rubin Report' To Ora TV |date=July 31, 2015 |website=HuffPost |publisher=AOL |first=Curtis |last=Wong |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810092511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/entry/dave-rubin-the-rubin-report_us_55b93fb5e4b095423d0dbad5 |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''[[The David Pakman Show]]'' \u2013 a political and current events radio show, hosted by [[David Pakman]], that began in 2005 and was affiliated with the TYT Network from 2012 to 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=David Pakman Joins The Young Turks Network |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/david-pakman-show-young-turks-cenk-uygur-ana-kasperian/172862 |first=Richard |last=Horgan |website=Adweek |date=May 31, 2012 |access-date=June 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402102556/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/david-pakman-show-young-turks-cenk-uygur-ana-kasperian/172862 |archive-date=April 2, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The Jimmy Dore Show'' \u2013 a commentary program hosted by stand-up comedian and political commentator [[Jimmy Dore]] that began in 2009 and was affiliated with the TYT Network from 2009 to 2019.\n\n== Political activity ==\nTYT promotes itself as the \"Home of Progressives\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Uygur has stated that \"TYT values journalistic objectivity\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> TYT commentary generates \"hybridized content\".<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> This involves TYT referencing news from mainstream sources and providing its own content analysis by connecting it to different narratives and discourses related to the social realities of its audience.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> The network's commentary has generated counter narratives in relation to traditional policy discussions.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> TYT places news in its context and connects it to the decision making process.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl192\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=192.}}</ref> By engaging with social movements, the station has called on its audience to became part of its \"TYT army\".<ref name=\"May506\">{{cite journal|last=May|first=Albert L.|title=Who tube? How YouTube's news and politics space is going mainstream|journal=The International Journal of Press/Politics|volume=15|issue=4|year=2010|pages=506|ref=harv|doi=10.1177/1940161210382861|citeseerx=10.1.1.1027.3801}}</ref> The network uses its platforms for advocacy, such as calling for its audience to participate in the political process and give candidates support.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> \n\nAs part of new media, TYT coverage conveys the frustration and discontent held by youth with the political system.<ref name=\"Solaimanxii\"/> Progressive social policies and liberal values are promoted through commentary by TYT.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Examples include TYT calling for [[Gun politics in the United States|gun control]] and the need to mitigate [[Police brutality in the United States|violence by police]] during its coverage of the 2018 [[Parkland school shooting]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> In similar coverage of [[Mass shootings in the United States|shootings]], TYT has provided information on [[Gun violence in the United States|gun and crime related homicide numbers]] and placed into context the [[Gun law in the United States|laws]], police training and additional factors that worsen the situation.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Hosts on TYT advocate for unionisation in large companies and the sharing of profits with their workers.<ref name=\"huffpostTYT\">[https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-young-turks-progressive-founder-urged-his-staff-not-to-unionize_n_5e540686c5b6ad3de3823a32 The Young Turks\u2019 Progressive Founder Urged His Staff Not To Unionize] By Dave Jamieson, The Huffington Post, February 24, 2020.</ref>  The network has spoken out against corruption in politics and for the need to remove corporate donations out of the political system.<ref name=\"Solaimanxii\">{{cite thesis|last=Solaiman|first=Barry|date=2017|title=Evaluating Lobbying in the United Kingdom: Moving from a Corruption Framework to 'Institutional Diversion'|type=Ph.D.|publisher=University of Cambridge|url=https://www.repository.cam.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/1810/269394/Solaiman-2017-PhD.pdf?sequence=1|access-date=24 February 2020|pages=xii|ref=harv}}</ref> The station has been critical of what it regards as a \"corporate coup\" in the US.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> TYT has criticised politicians from the US [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] for alleged attachment to financial interests and for appearing to be progressive.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> Hosts on TYT have called for the Democratic Party to undergo a revitalisation process.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The network has been critical of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] (TPP) trade deal and its supporters like Hillary Clinton, whereas TYT approved of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]' opposition to it.<ref name=\"Marmura100\"/> The station has defended the [[whistleblower]] [[WikiLeaks]] organisation and its data disclosures on several issues such as the TPP, the [[DNC email leak]] and the [[Hillary Clinton email controversy]].<ref name=\"Marmura87100115\">{{harvnb|Marmura|2018|pp=87, 100, 115.}}</ref> TYT was sceptical about claims of alleged [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian interference in the 2016 US presidential election]].<ref name=\"Marmura115123\">{{cite book|last=Marmura|first=Stephen M. E.|title=The WikiLeaks Paradigm: Paradoxes and Revelations|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319971391|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iE1tDwAAQBAJ&pg=PP5&dq=The+WikiLeaks+Paradigm:+Paradoxes+and+Revelations#v=onepage&q=TYT&f=false|pages=115, 123|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe station uses traditional and online media platforms regarding political action and mobilisation for citizen engagement with institutional politics.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/><ref name=\"Marmura100\">{{harvnb|Marmura|2018|p=100.}}</ref> For example, TYT townhalls are hosted in local communities involving a moderator asking questions of the expert panel followed by audience questions, with the events streamed on Youtube and on-demand web access for its subscription membership.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl186\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=186}}</ref> Viewers also have the option to send video questions to the network if they are unable to be present at the townhall.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> TYT townhall events involve detailed commentary by hosts and guests on political topics ranging from personal experiences to abstract notions on issues of concern that serve to connect their audience and lived experiences with politics.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> During the 2016 US presidential election, TYT hosted townhalls with Sanders and [[Green Party of the United States|Green party]] candidate [[Jill Stein]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\"/> In the late 2010s, other TYT townhalls were held with Sanders on the [[Climate change mitigation|climate change crisis]].<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl188\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=188.}}</ref> Several hosts for TYT have expressed support for Sanders.<ref name=\"Taylor204\">{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=J. Benjamin|title=Extreme Media and American Politics: In Defense of Extremity|year=2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319411835|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4VqXDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Extreme+Media+and+American+Politics:+In+Defense+of+Extremity#v=snippet&q=Young%20Turks&f=false|pages=204|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Kolehmainen22\">{{cite journal|last=Kolehmainen|first=Pekka|title=Social media narratives as political fan fiction in the 2016 US presidential election|journal=European Journal of American Studies|volume=12|issue=12\u20132|year=2017|ref=harv|doi=10.4000/ejas.12147}} para. 22.</ref><ref name=\"Hellinger109\">{{cite book|last=Hellinger|first=Daniel C.|title=Conspiracies and Conspiracy Theories in the Age of Trump|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319981581|url=https://books.google.com/?id=U3hvDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Conspiracies+and+Conspiracy+Theories+in+the+Age+of+Trump#v=onepage&q=uygur&f=false|pages=109|ref=harv}}</ref> \n\n[[File:TYT Medicare For All sign (48434414206).jpg|thumb|250px|TYT sign supporting [[Medicare for All]]]]\nThe network supports political candidates who are from the same ideological persuasion.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> Following the 2016 presidential election, Uygur co-founded Justice Democrats, an organisation that seeks to get progressive candidates elected into office.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\"/> During the US mid-term elections (2018), the network endorsed all candidates from the Justice Democrats (JD).<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\"/> TYT was the first network to give airtime to progressive candidates such as [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] to discuss policies and contrast themselves from electoral opponents on its shows like ''Rebel HQ'', a half an hour interview based program created in 2017.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\"/> In 2018, TYT also featured other progressive political candidates on ''Rebel HQ'' such as [[Richard Ojeda]] during his congressional run, gubernatorial candidates [[Cynthia Nixon]] who ran in [[New York (state)|New York State]] and [[Christine Hallquist]] in [[Vermont]] to discuss their policies.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\"/> \n\nAs a platform for online and offline civic engagement and political action, ''Rebel HQ'' offers information about a candidate, their website and campaign.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\"/> The show informs viewers on how they can contact politicians, assist progressive candidates affiliated or unaffiliated with the Justice Democrats through donations or to participate by volunteering, canvassing and attending events like rallies in local communities.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191192\">{{cite book|last1=Grigoryan|first1=Nune|last2=Suetzl|first2=Wolfgang|chapter=Hybridized political participation|editor1-last=Atkinson|editor1-first=Joshua D.|editor2-last=Kenix|editor2-first=Linda|title=Alternative Media Meets Mainstream Politics: Activist Nation Rising|year=2019|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781498584357|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D_CYDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Alternative+Media+Meets+Mainstream+Politics:+Activist+Nation+Rising#v=snippet&q=TYT&f=false|pages=190, 191\u2013192|ref=harv}}</ref> TYT's online platforms facilitate the encouragement of civic participation with the political system that in 2018 assisted Justice Democrats in getting 7 congressional victories, 25 candidates during the general election and 78 in the primaries.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl191\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=191.}}</ref> After Ocasio-Cortez became a congresswomen, TYT has continued to cover and defend her from slants by the political and media elite.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|p=190}}</ref> Other Justice Democrats congressional members like [[Ro Khanna]] and [[Rashida Tlaib]] have appeared on TYT discussing progressive policies and issues.<ref name=\"GrigoryanSuetzl190191\">{{harvnb|Grigoryan|Suetzl|2019|pp=190-191.}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, during a high-profile Democratic presidential candidate campaign weekend in Iowa, TYT and a group of supporters launched the Progressive Economic Pledge campaign, challenging presidential candidates to sign. The pledge is to support higher wages, Medicare for All, Green New Deal, college for all and the end of private campaign financing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/448565-young-turks-founder-voting-for-biden-over-trump-would-be-no-brainer|title=Young Turks founder: Voting for Biden over Trump would be 'no-brainer'|last=Bonn|first=Tess|date=2019-06-14|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713182146/https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/448565-young-turks-founder-voting-for-biden-over-trump-would-be-no-brainer|archive-date=July 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://join.tyt.com/pledge/|title=Join TYT\"s Progressive Economic Pledge|website=join.tyt.com|access-date=2019-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629084940/https://join.tyt.com/pledge/|archive-date=June 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-November 2019, Uygur filed to run for Congress in [[California's 25th congressional district|California's 25th district]], a seat recently vacated by the resignation of [[Katie Hill (politician)|Katie Hill]], an office also being pursued by former Trump campaign aide [[George Papadopoulos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/election-2020/cenk-uygur-files-to-run-for-congress-in-katie-hills-district/|title=Cenk Uygur Files to Run For Congress in Katie Hill's District|date=2019-11-13|website=Mediaite|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/cenk-uygur-young-turks-files-run-congresswoman-katie-hills-seat-one-day-after-endorsing-1471638|title=Cenk Uygur of 'The Young Turks' files to run for Congresswoman Katie Hill's seat one day after endorsing Sanders|last=Malaea|first=Marika|date=2019-11-13|website=Newsweek|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/cenk-uygur-congress-run-katie-hill-california|title=Liberal host Cenk Uygur files for congressional run in Katie Hill's former district|last=Wulfsohn|first=Joseph|date=2019-11-13|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> Uygur as a result took a leave of absence while campaigning but continued to make appearances as co-host during designated breaks in his campaign schedule, with Kasparian acting as the executive producer and assuming editorial control of the program during this timeframe.\n\n== Name controversy ==\n\nAccording to Cenk Uygur, the name of the show was chosen because it is a popular colloquialism traditionally meaning a young radical who fights the status quo.<ref name=\"pastemagazine\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/01/why-cenk-uygur-is-getting-confronted-about-the-nam.html |title=Why Cenk Uygur Is Getting Confronted about the Name \"The Young Turks,\" and Why It Matters |first=Monica |last=Hunter-Hart |date=January 5, 2017 |magazine=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328230829/https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/01/why-cenk-uygur-is-getting-confronted-about-the-nam.html |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the American Heritage Dictionary, it stands for \"a young progressive or insurgent member of an institution, movement, or political party.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=young+turk&submit.x=0&submit.y=0 |title=Young Turk |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Publishing Company |website=The American Heritage Dictionary |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328215243/https://ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=young+turk&submit.x=0&submit.y=0 |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Safire |first=William |title=Safire's Political Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |date=2008 |page=826 |isbn=978-0195343342}}</ref> The phrase has a history of being used in Western politics. It was used by [[Young Turks (U.S. politics)|a rebellious group of Congressmen]] within the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], of which [[Gerald Ford]] was a prominent member, who had become disenchanted with the course of the Party during the early 1960s as well as other [[Young Turks (disambiguation)|political groups around the world]]. However, the Young Turks show has been criticized for the name, as the original [[Young Turks]] political movement in the Ottoman Empire committed the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\"pastemagazine\"/> and that in 1991 Cenk Uygur wrote an article in ''[[The Daily Pennsylvanian]]'' in which he promoted Armenian Genocide denial.<ref>Uygur, Cenk (November 20, 1991). {{cite web |url=https://dparchives.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/pennsylvania?a=d&d=tdp19911122-01.2.24 |title=Historical Fact or Falsehood? The Daily Pennsylvanian Digital Archives |access-date=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406114936/https://dparchives.library.upenn.edu/cgi-bin/pennsylvania?a=d&d=tdp19911122-01.2.24 |archive-date=April 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2016, he rescinded these statements, arguing: \"My mistake at the time was confusing myself for a scholar of history, which I most certainly am not. I don\u2019t want to make the same mistake again, so I am going to refrain from commenting on the topic of the Armenian Genocide, which I do not know nearly enough about.\"<ref>[https://legacy.tyt.com/2016/04/22/rescinding-daily-pennsylvanian-article/ Rescinding Daily Pennsylvanian Article] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626085246/https://legacy.tyt.com/2016/04/22/rescinding-daily-pennsylvanian-article/ |date=June 26, 2019 }} Cenk Uygur, TYT Network; April 22, 2016</ref> Cenk Uygur has admitted to being mistaken about the Armenian Genocide and has recognized it as historical fact.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cenk Uygur recognizing Armenian Genocide |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-Xib49Opls0 |publisher=Haypress News}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|The Young Turks}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.tyt.com/}}\n* {{YouTube|u=TheYoungTurks|The Young Turks}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Free Talk Live]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Podcast Awards|Podcast Award]] for<br/>Best Political Podcast/Best Political Website|years=2009}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Free Talk Live]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TYT Network}}\n{{Current TV}}\n{{AAR}}\n{{Streamy Awards Winners CSS}}\n{{Portal bar|Internet|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young Turks, The}}\n[[Category:The Young Turks (talk show)| ]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Liberalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:California media]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:American talk radio programs]]\n[[Category:2002 radio programme debuts]]\n[[Category:Internet television channels]]\n[[Category:Digital media]]\n[[Category:American web series]]\n[[Category:Non-fiction web series]]\n[[Category:2005 web series debuts]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels]]\n[[Category:Multi-channel networks]]\n[[Category:Streamy Award-winning channels, series or shows]]\n[[Category:2010s American television news programs]]\n[[Category:2011 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Current TV original programming]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:YouTube channels launched in 2005]]\n", "name_user": "AlexWall07", "label": "safe", "comment": "