st League}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1960\u201361 in European association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1960\u201361 in Yugoslavian football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n  | competition        = [[Yugoslav First League|Prva savezna liga]]\n  | season             = 1960&ndash;61\n  | dates = {{Nowrap|18 September 1960 \u2013 11 June 1961}}\n  | winners            = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] (3rd title)\n  | runners-up         = \n  | promoted           = \n  | relegated          = [[RNK Split]]<br />[[FK Radni\u010dki Jugopetrol|Radni\u010dki Belgrade]]\n  | continentalcup1    = [[1961\u201362 European Cup|European Cup]]\n  | continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n  | continentalcup2    = [[1961\u201362 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n  | continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[FK Vardar|Vardar]]\n  | continentalcup3    = [[1961\u201362 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]\n  | continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]<br />[[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]<br />[[FK Vojvodina|Vojvodina]]\n  | league topscorer   = [[Zoran Prljin\u010devi\u0107]]<br />[[Todor Veselinovi\u0107]]<br /> (16 goals each)\n  | biggest home win   = \n  | biggest away win   = \n  | highest scoring    = \n  | total goals        = \n  | average goals      = \n  | longest wins       = \n  | longest unbeaten   = \n  | longest losses     = \n  | highest attendance = \n  | lowest attendance  = \n  | average attendance = \n  | prevseason         = [[1959\u201360 Yugoslav First League|1959\u201360]]\n  | nextseason         = [[1961\u201362 Yugoslav First League|1961\u201362]]\n}}\nThe '''1960\u201361 Yugoslav First League season''' was won by FK Partizan, which was the club's third title and its first in twelve years. The season was also a coming-out party of sorts for the club's talented new generation of young players known as \"Partizan's babies\" that would dominate Yugoslav football for the next few years and would even go on to make it to the 1966 European Cup final.\n\nThe season began later than usual in order to accommodate the [[Yugoslavia Olympic football team|Yugoslav Olympic national team]]'s late August and early September 1960 participation at the [[Football at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960 Rome Olympics]] where they won the gold medal with a roster [[Football at the 1960 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men%27s team squads#Yugoslavia|consisting entirely]] of players from the Yugoslav First League.\n\n==Teams==\nAt the end of the previous season [[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]] and [[FK Sloboda Tuzla|Sloboda]] were relegated. They were replaced by [[FK Vardar|Vardar]] and [[RNK Split]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n!width=\"130\"| Team\n!width=\"100\"| Location\n!width=\"200\"| [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia#Federal subjects|Federal Republic]] \n!width=\"90\"| Position<br />in [[1959\u201360 Yugoslav First League|1959\u201360]]\n|-\n|[[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">002</span>2nd\n|-\n|[[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n|[[Split (city)|Split]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">005</span>5th\n|-\n|[[OFK Beograd|OFK Belgrade]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">007</span>7th\n|-\n|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">003</span>3rd\n|-\n|[[FK Radni\u010dki Jugopetrol|Radni\u010dki Belgrade]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">009</span>9th\n|-\n|[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"gold\"|<span style=\"display:none\">001</span>1st\n|-\n|[[NK Rijeka|Rijeka]]\n|[[Rijeka]]\n|{{f